{"term":"1956","caseName":"United States v. Witkovich","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/295","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 28, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13214","transcript":[{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I would like to reserve it for rebuttal.","start":0,"stop":7.909,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Hart.","start":7.909,"stop":12.106,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":12.106,"stop":15.294,"duration":3.19},{"text":"I would like to say at the threshold that it is all together likely that this case would not be before Your Honors and I would not be here this afternoon if I had advised my client to plead the Fifth Amendment in relation to the questions which were asked of him.","start":15.294,"stop":33.188,"duration":17.89},{"text":"But the integrity of the client and devotion to the proper administration of the law did not permit us to indulge in any subterfuges.","start":33.188,"stop":44.532,"duration":11.34},{"text":"And therefore, whatever answers we refuse to give, our position was that the questions were in violation of our rights under the First Amendment and also that the questions were not pertinent to any issue.","start":44.532,"stop":60.356,"duration":15.82},{"text":"And we feel that we have a complete right to protection for ourselves under the First Amendment just as much as we have under any other amendment to the Constitution.","start":60.356,"stop":75.352,"duration":15},{"text":"I would like to say too that briefly on the question of the right of supervision because that's the point, I think, in which we left that the kind of supervision attempted here would be all together feudal under almost any circumstances that we can conceive.","start":75.352,"stop":94.034,"duration":18.68},{"text":"For instance, if this defendant, when called upon by the person in the Naturalization Service, had bared his life completely from the cradle to the present time and had told all about himself, and nevertheless said, \"Yes, I still am a member of the Communist Party and I still go to meetings of the Communist Party.\"","start":94.034,"stop":119.292,"duration":25.26},{"text":"What assistance would that had been to the Attorney General in the so-called supervision or what could the Attorney General have done having that information before him?","start":119.292,"stop":131.627,"duration":12.34},{"text":"On the other hand, suppose the defendant had taken the position that he refused to answer on the basis of the Fifth Amendment, how would the Attorney General have been assisted in this so-called supervision of the defendant.","start":131.627,"stop":145.697,"duration":14.07},{"text":"In neither event, would anything happen then, it would have been a feudal act as far as the order supervision is concerned.","start":145.697,"stop":154.515,"duration":8.82},{"text":"And while that should not be determinative of the entire proposition, nevertheless, on the mere argument of the supervision, it gets the Court nowhere in my opinion.","start":154.515,"stop":167.934,"duration":13.42},{"text":"Another matter to which I want to call your attention preliminarily is this, that there is nothing in the indictment and the indictment has to be considered, I believe, by this Court from its four corners.","start":167.934,"stop":181.471,"duration":13.54},{"text":"There's nothing in the indictment which has any reference at all to Communist Party membership or engaging in Communist and activities.","start":181.471,"stop":191.052,"duration":9.58},{"text":"It is a general indictment which says that the defendant who is then and there and the alien against whom an order of deportation had issued and been outstanding for more than six months, which said order of deportation was then and there, a final order having become final on a certain day and who is the project from the United States under the order of deportation had not been affected with in such six-month period and who was then and there pending eventual deportation subject to supervision was required to come in and answer questions, et cetera and he refused to answer the following questions.","start":191.052,"stop":224.18,"duration":33.13},{"text":"Now, are we to assume, and I'm not making a great point over because I suppose you might as well meet the whole situation squarely, are we to assume from this that all of these matters in relation to Communist Party activity are pertinent to this particular kind of an indictment because there's nothing in it.","start":224.18,"stop":242.605,"duration":18.42},{"text":"Now then, they proceed to give the questions which it was said he refused to answer.","start":242.605,"stop":248.439,"duration":5.83},{"text":"And the first question you will notice is, \"Do you subscribe to the Daily Worker?\"","start":248.439,"stop":253.727,"duration":5.29},{"text":"I would like to tell you, and that does happened to be part of the record, that the question which immediately preceeded it was, \"Do you rate the Chicago Daily Tribune?\"","start":253.727,"stop":264.041,"duration":10.31},{"text":"Well, of course, we objected to answering that under the First Amendment just the same as we objected to answering in regard to the Daily Worker.","start":264.041,"stop":271.503,"duration":7.46},{"text":"However, we're not being embedded for not answering as to whether we read the Daily Tribune or not.","start":271.503,"stop":278.415,"duration":6.91},{"text":"All of these questions -- I think there are 22 questions contained in the indictment which we --","start":278.415,"stop":285.631,"duration":7.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask in part whether --","start":285.631,"stop":287.465,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon.","start":287.465,"stop":287.718,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Any other that you refused to answer that demand -- are the substantive methods to --","start":287.718,"stop":293.669,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I believe there are.","start":293.669,"stop":295.425,"duration":1.76},{"text":"I --","start":295.425,"stop":295.902,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they --","start":295.902,"stop":296.606,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I can't point them out at this moment unless I go through the entire series of questions, Your Honor.","start":296.606,"stop":301.636,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The scope of that, are there references?","start":301.636,"stop":303.817,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":303.817,"stop":304.222,"duration":0.4},{"text":"It's all in -- in the record and the -- all of the questions, Your Honor, we'll find on page -- beginning on page 32 of the transcript.","start":304.222,"stop":318.002,"duration":13.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":318.002,"stop":322.155,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Ninety five questions in total were asked.","start":322.155,"stop":327.912,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"And he refused to answer?","start":327.912,"stop":330.282,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"And he refused to answer 22.","start":330.282,"stop":332.97,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"If this number amounts to more than (Inaudible)","start":332.97,"stop":337.948,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he refused to answer that too, Your Honor, because we saw no purpose of it as to whether or not he could translate or read several languages.","start":337.948,"stop":346.521,"duration":8.57},{"text":"We felt he had no pertinency at all to the proposition of this having to be deported.","start":346.521,"stop":352.511,"duration":5.99},{"text":"We thought there was no pertinency to a number of other questions which were asked now.","start":352.511,"stop":357.585,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean to make a point of it, I just want knowledge.","start":357.585,"stop":363.466,"duration":5.88},{"text":"Some of them -- some of the questions were answered?","start":363.466,"stop":366.326,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Some of the questions were answered.","start":366.326,"stop":368.496,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And was a line drawn then or is a line drawn now by you?","start":368.496,"stop":373.017,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the line was drawn at that time and we said at that time that certain questions we refused to answer because either they were a violation of the First Amendment or they were not pertinent to any right that the Attorney General had or to any issue which was involved.","start":373.017,"stop":389.258,"duration":16.24},{"text":"That was done at the time of the questioning and there is nothing new added to it at this time, Your Honor.","start":389.258,"stop":395.826,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if -- I've heard that there was a counsel present.","start":395.826,"stop":400.303,"duration":4.48},{"text":"Were you the counsel present --","start":400.303,"stop":400.897,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I was counsel --","start":400.897,"stop":401.605,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- so that --","start":401.605,"stop":401.707,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- present at that time.","start":401.707,"stop":403.623,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and I don't think counsel will stop by anything they do to protect through their clients.","start":403.623,"stop":408.758,"duration":5.13},{"text":"Is it your position now that some of the questions are pertinent?","start":408.758,"stop":412.346,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I have no hesitancy as to that.","start":412.346,"stop":414.819,"duration":2.47},{"text":"And for instance, you will find that we answered about 70 questions which have to do with these matters, \"Where do you live?","start":414.819,"stop":422.62,"duration":7.8},{"text":"Do you own a property?","start":422.62,"stop":423.88,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Where do you work?","start":423.88,"stop":424.572,"duration":0.69},{"text":"How many hours a day do you work?","start":424.572,"stop":426.074,"duration":1.5},{"text":"What do you do with your spare time?","start":426.074,"stop":427.595,"duration":1.52},{"text":"How many children have you, have your wife?","start":427.595,"stop":430.205,"duration":2.61},{"text":"We have five children, we have a wife.","start":430.205,"stop":432.35,"duration":2.15},{"text":"They are all born in the United States.","start":432.35,"stop":435.078,"duration":2.73},{"text":"One son was a member of the Armed Forces.","start":435.078,"stop":438.626,"duration":3.55},{"text":"All of those questions which have anything to do with the possibility of putting a hand on the individual as soon as deportation is possible were answered.","start":438.626,"stop":451.382,"duration":12.76},{"text":"At no time, did the Attorney General have to guess about our location or whereabouts, the place of employment, how much we earn, whether we own real estate, how much the mortgages on the real estate.","start":451.382,"stop":463.199,"duration":11.82},{"text":"We have no --","start":463.199,"stop":463.745,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All these -- all these I infer from what you've just said, it seemed to you pertinent to the question where they feel available in case he -- or whether you like it to be -- likely to flee, is that right?","start":463.745,"stop":474.354,"duration":10.61}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":474.354,"stop":475.782,"duration":1.43},{"text":"And I had no hesitancy in advising him to answer all those questions which would properly inform the Attorney General where he was at all times, although of course, the Attorney General knows where he is anyway but I had no purpose.","start":475.782,"stop":489.425,"duration":13.64},{"text":"Now, when they asked this, \"Do you know so and so, John Smith, William Jones, et cetera, et cetera?\"","start":489.425,"stop":494.449,"duration":5.02},{"text":"I don't know who those people are, but we also felt that they were not pertinent to any right which the Attorney General had.","start":494.449,"stop":500.751,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Why?","start":500.751,"stop":501.602,"duration":0.85},{"text":"Because he told what labor union he belonged to.","start":501.602,"stop":504.98,"duration":3.38},{"text":"He told where he worked and that he's been working there for two years and more.","start":504.98,"stop":508.56,"duration":3.58},{"text":"He told where he lived, where he earned property and where his children and wife lives.","start":508.56,"stop":512.635,"duration":4.07},{"text":"So that there was no difficulty on the part of the Attorney General at any moment at all to locate him and we felt that that was all that was necessary.","start":512.635,"stop":521.491,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Now, of course, we wouldn't have been heard if we had told him whether we can speak more than one language.","start":521.491,"stop":527.315,"duration":5.82},{"text":"And we wouldn't have been heard if we had told him whether we read the Tribune or the Daily Worker.","start":527.315,"stop":532.884,"duration":5.57},{"text":"But on the question of principle and viewing to the line, we felt he had no right to ask those questions.","start":532.884,"stop":538.952,"duration":6.07},{"text":"And therefore, we refused to answer on the two grounds like the pertinency and also the First Amendment which we trust this Court.","start":538.952,"stop":548.731,"duration":9.78},{"text":"We'll consider it in relation to the -- the whole situation.","start":548.731,"stop":553.324,"duration":4.59},{"text":"Now, Your Honors, there --","start":553.324,"stop":554.572,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Hart, is there anything in the record that shows that the next move is in accordance with their activity (Inaudible) of their activities?","start":554.572,"stop":563.958,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean his activity outside of his occupation?","start":563.958,"stop":566.05,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean plaintiff here.","start":566.05,"stop":567.392,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Do you --","start":567.392,"stop":567.841,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I do not know and there's nothing in the record at all to indicate who they are.","start":567.841,"stop":572.228,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know who Leo Fisher is?","start":572.228,"stop":573.673,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I would not.","start":573.673,"stop":575.279,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Now, whether he knew, I'm not in position to say it.","start":575.279,"stop":577.534,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's not in the record.","start":577.534,"stop":578.766,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not -- there's nothing in the record about that at all.","start":578.766,"stop":582.043,"duration":3.28},{"text":"Now, when they asked him, \"Do you know the editor of so-and-so?\"","start":582.043,"stop":585.466,"duration":3.42},{"text":"We think that's impertinent to the issue.","start":585.466,"stop":588.15,"duration":2.68},{"text":"When they asked him, \"What is the policy of the newspaper for which you worked as a pressman?\"","start":588.15,"stop":593.463,"duration":5.31},{"text":"We refused to answer because that has no pertinency to anything.","start":593.463,"stop":597.556,"duration":4.09},{"text":"And certainly, we're -- we're not required to know what the policy of a newspaper is for whom we work merely as a pressman.","start":597.556,"stop":604.209,"duration":6.65},{"text":"So all down the line, we distinguish between those things which we felt that the Attorney General had a proper right to inquire into -- in those things which had no pertinency to the issue.","start":604.209,"stop":615.533,"duration":11.32},{"text":"And on the question of Communist Party membership, if the Court please, precisely the same thing, and as far as the First Amendment is concerned, we think we have a complete right to rely on the protection of the First Amendment in connection with that.","start":615.533,"stop":629.691,"duration":14.16},{"text":"But as I said a moment ago, supposed he had said that he was still a member or suppose he had taken the fifth and said, \"It's none of your business because the fifth protects me.\"","start":629.691,"stop":640.17,"duration":10.48},{"text":"What would have availed the Attorney General in respect for that?","start":640.17,"stop":644.038,"duration":3.87},{"text":"Now, those are just by way of preliminary, if Your Honors please.","start":644.038,"stop":648.407,"duration":4.37},{"text":"And I would like, if I possibly can to go into a summary of the other matters which we relate -- indicate the miscellaneous frailties in the whole situation.","start":648.407,"stop":663.885,"duration":15.48},{"text":"The statute itself or that Section of the statute itself, it cannot, in my humble opinion, be regarded as a constitutionally collectible because it is so vague that it's impossible for anybody to judge what is intended by.","start":663.885,"stop":689.227,"duration":25.34},{"text":"And that provides at any --","start":689.227,"stop":690.878,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your relevance made a judgment on seven questions out of nine.","start":690.878,"stop":694.714,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon, sir.","start":694.714,"stop":695.961,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On the question of vagueness --","start":695.961,"stop":697.406,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":697.406,"stop":697.485,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you eminently made a judgment of the relevance of seven questions out of nine.","start":697.485,"stop":704.198,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, even if that were so, the -- my judgment as to what was irrelevant had to do with the particular questions which were asked at that time.","start":704.198,"stop":715.994,"duration":11.8},{"text":"But in considering the Section of the statute itself, I think, if Your Honor please, that -- if I wanted to know other failing, I think, than this, and such other information whether or not related to the foregoing as the Attorney General may deem fit and proper, I think that if nothing else should cause that particular section to be struck.","start":715.994,"stop":745.578,"duration":29.58},{"text":"I equate this particular Section with such matters as refusal to answer questions before a congressional committee.","start":745.578,"stop":754.005,"duration":8.43},{"text":"That's a similar situation.","start":754.005,"stop":756.581,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I also find similarity between this kind of a situation and one in where -- in which a person is called to testify before a grand jury or before our court and refuses to do so.","start":756.581,"stop":770.535,"duration":13.95},{"text":"But in those other cases, if Your Honors please, there are protective devices placed about the individual so that he doesn't stand alone in a vacuum and no matter what he does may result in his imprisonment.","start":770.535,"stop":783.229,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if Judge Sullivan's construction of the statute could find favor then these difficulties do not arise, do they?","start":783.229,"stop":791.417,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":791.417,"stop":792.294,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, don't we have to address ourselves first to the question whether his construction is either instinctively called for or called for by our rule if you don't go into constitutionality if you can save it.","start":792.294,"stop":806.378,"duration":14.08}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now I -- I'll try to limit myself for the present to that situation.","start":806.378,"stop":813.394,"duration":7.02},{"text":"This matter came before Judge Sullivan on two occasions on a motion to dismiss the indictment because it didn't allege a crime.","start":813.394,"stop":823.676,"duration":10.28},{"text":"We took the position that mere failure to talk was not a crime unless something else attended it.","start":823.676,"stop":829.88,"duration":6.2},{"text":"In his first opinion, he -- we also argued that the law was unconstitutional.","start":829.88,"stop":837.382,"duration":7.5},{"text":"In his first opinion, he said that he felt that the law was constitutional but that the questions which were asked had to be determined on the question of relevancy.","start":837.382,"stop":850.009,"duration":12.63},{"text":"And that was all that was in the opinion.","start":850.009,"stop":853.321,"duration":3.31},{"text":"That apparently was a considerable disappointment to the Government because they came in with the petitioner asking the Court to clarify his opinion.","start":853.321,"stop":862.062,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I -- may I ask this because I'm puzzled.","start":862.062,"stop":865.978,"duration":3.92},{"text":"Suppose nothing had been done, what would have been -- what -- what would have followed the original memorandum or opinion of Judge Sullivan?","start":865.978,"stop":874.555,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"If nothing more had been done?","start":874.555,"stop":875.884,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if the Government hadn't come in for clarification and you hadn't come in for dismissal of the indictment.","start":875.884,"stop":881.267,"duration":5.38},{"text":"What would have been the course of things?","start":881.267,"stop":884.185,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"My course would have been precisely the same thing that I did.","start":884.185,"stop":887.841,"duration":3.66},{"text":"I would have gone in, in response to his opinion and asked the Court to determine from the indictment, which of these questions were relevant as the Court put it.","start":887.841,"stop":897.984,"duration":10.14},{"text":"And I did that, Your Honor.","start":897.984,"stop":900.216,"duration":2.23},{"text":"And I would have done it whether the Government had asked for a clarification.","start":900.216,"stop":904.02,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what was -- I'm a little puzzled by it.","start":904.02,"stop":907.735,"duration":3.72},{"text":"What was the implication of his opinion?","start":907.735,"stop":910.066,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Did he expect the Government then to move for a trial and have the question of relevance determined at the trial?","start":910.066,"stop":916.754,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I can only give my personal opinion.","start":916.754,"stop":919.922,"duration":3.17},{"text":"I think he felt that a trial would have ensued.","start":919.922,"stop":922.613,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because if this is -- intellectual curiosity more than anything else which directs some question.","start":922.613,"stop":927.406,"duration":4.79},{"text":"A very surprising thing that a judge should be asked to tell what he meant.","start":927.406,"stop":931.697,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the Government's fault.","start":931.697,"stop":933.682,"duration":1.99},{"text":"I -- I don't care if that --","start":933.682,"stop":934.229,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not blaming or -- or praising us.","start":934.229,"stop":937.155,"duration":2.93},{"text":"It seemed to me he'd left and sort it up in the air, didn't he?","start":937.155,"stop":939.816,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and that's why I say that the Government was rather disturbed about it.","start":939.816,"stop":944.366,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Now, under Rule 12 where the federal rules of criminal procedure, a court has a right to determine if it's possible or whether or not there is something to be done prior to the trial.","start":944.366,"stop":955.304,"duration":10.94},{"text":"On the second argument before Judge Sullivan, we went into the specific questions which were asked and Judge Sullivan, as Your Honors will note from his opinion, could not say that any of the questions, about which the indictment was brought in, were relevant to the defendant's availability for deportation.","start":955.304,"stop":979.216,"duration":23.91},{"text":"And on the basis of that, he dismissed the indictment.","start":979.216,"stop":983.953,"duration":4.74},{"text":"I -- I think the federal court was correct in that opinion because he saw all of the questions which were asked and he doubtless must have compared these specific questions which we refused to answer to those which we had answered and he must have known from those which we answered that the Attorney General had all possible available information as to where this man lived and what he did so that he could be seized at anytime that deportation was possible.","start":983.953,"stop":1018.356,"duration":34.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what he did the second time, am I wrong about this?","start":1018.356,"stop":1022.495,"duration":4.14},{"text":"After you -- after your motion for clarification, he then ruled on the meaning of the statute, namely, the questions must relate to availability as in (Inaudible) the indictment and said not one of these questions relates to that topic and therefore, you haven't stated out of offense and therefore, the indictment were to be dismissed.","start":1022.495,"stop":1042.912,"duration":20.42},{"text":"And I should think that followed logically from -- from the scope that he gave to the statute, isn't that right?","start":1042.912,"stop":1048.749,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":1048.749,"stop":1050.454,"duration":1.7},{"text":"And the indictment was dismissed and we're from the Government, of course, appealed and I, representing the defendant, felt that since the Government had brought an appeal that this did present an opportunity to the defendant to present other issues before this Court, which I hope the Court will consider, although, I'm fully aware of the fact that the Court will not consider constitutional issues if there are other issues which are available for the adjudication of a case.","start":1050.454,"stop":1085.161,"duration":34.71},{"text":"Personally, I regret it but I'm on -- on the Court.","start":1085.161,"stop":1087.341,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Now, if the Court please --","start":1087.341,"stop":1088.733,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You might not if you were on the Court.","start":1088.733,"stop":1090.36,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1090.36,"stop":1093.109,"duration":2.75},{"text":"At least you're right.","start":1093.109,"stop":1098.461,"duration":5.35},{"text":"The final words of Judge Sullivan were these.","start":1098.461,"stop":1102.322,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Under the statutory, the questions must be relevant to the congressional power to legislate.","start":1102.322,"stop":1108.184,"duration":5.86},{"text":"As in the instant case, they must relate to the valid power of the Attorney General, the motion to dismiss the -- wait a minute, I'm sorry, I'm reading the wrong one.","start":1108.184,"stop":1123.738,"duration":15.55},{"text":"Well, at any rate, I recounted without using the language of the Court that the motion to dismiss the indictment was granted and as a result thereof, we are here.","start":1123.738,"stop":1135.628,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Now, if Your Honors please, I -- I think one of the very important and difficult questions to determine here is the validity constitutionally of the Section itself.","start":1135.628,"stop":1150.237,"duration":14.61},{"text":"You have a man who cannot be deported because no country will take him.","start":1150.237,"stop":1156.328,"duration":6.09},{"text":"With reference to the Carlson case which was referred to earlier, that case is the size of -- of a situation during the first six months subsequent to an order of deportation.","start":1156.328,"stop":1168.92,"duration":12.59},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, the Court held that the Court have a right to review the discretion of the Attorney General in refusing bill.","start":1168.92,"stop":1179.962,"duration":11.04},{"text":"After the six-month period is over, the deportee may not be held under bail but he has to be discharged and the practice is, in all of these cases, that his bail has returned to him and he goes home but he's called in to sign if he will and most of the time, he won't, a supervisory parole agreement under which these various things are set up.","start":1179.962,"stop":1207.325,"duration":27.36},{"text":"And the law provides that he has to submit to physical and psychiatric examination at the discretion of the Attorney General that he may not associate with persons who are Communist and originally the supervisory agreement even included a wife but they have made an exception since that, if the Court please.","start":1207.325,"stop":1235.063,"duration":27.74},{"text":"Then, he shall give information under oath as to his nationality, circumstances have it, associations and activities and such other information whether or not related to the foregoing as the Attorney General may deem fit and proper and to conform to such reasonable different restrictions on his convict or activities as are prescribed by the Attorney General in his case.","start":1235.063,"stop":1254.862,"duration":19.8},{"text":"And here is the crux of it.","start":1254.862,"stop":1256.814,"duration":1.95},{"text":"Any alien who shall willfully fail to comply with such regulations, or willfully failed to appear or to give information or submit to medical or psychiatric examination if required, or knowingly give false information in relation to the requirements of such regulations, or knowingly violate a reasonable restriction imposed upon his convict or activity shall account conviction be guilty of the felony.","start":1256.814,"stop":1282.794,"duration":25.98},{"text":"That has since been changed to misdemeanor and shall be fined not more than $1000 or shall be imprisoned not more than one year or both.","start":1282.794,"stop":1292.555,"duration":9.76},{"text":"To me, it seems that the terminal points of what a person may or may not do are all together undetermined in this section of the statute.","start":1292.555,"stop":1301.905,"duration":9.35},{"text":"I have to --","start":1301.905,"stop":1303.567,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What you said were -- were supervisory agreement, is that something that maybe within six months or --","start":1303.567,"stop":1310.228,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"The supervisory agreement, Your Honor, is subsequent to the six-month period and is given to the deportee when his bail is returned to him.","start":1310.228,"stop":1321.933,"duration":11.7},{"text":"And he asked us to sign that he will refrain from doing certain things that he will not commit any offense under the Smith Act.","start":1321.933,"stop":1330.085,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the ordinary part of this that they will not part?","start":1330.085,"stop":1333.599,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1333.599,"stop":1334.759,"duration":1.16},{"text":"We take the position, if Your Honor please, that the statute does not provide, that it has to be signed by the deportee and therefore, the deportee does not sign it.","start":1334.759,"stop":1343.985,"duration":9.23},{"text":"And it is read to him.","start":1343.985,"stop":1345.335,"duration":1.35},{"text":"A copy is handed to him so in that way he has notice of it, but he -- he does not agree to it by signing it as the questions do.","start":1345.335,"stop":1355.992,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any such conditions in his release on bail during that six months period, Ms. Hart?","start":1355.992,"stop":1362.563,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to be held to this, Your Honor, but I think the only condition on his release on bail is that he shall present himself for deportation when called for.","start":1362.563,"stop":1374.031,"duration":11.47},{"text":"Now, there may be other situations where they incorporate other conditions.","start":1374.031,"stop":1378.229,"duration":4.2},{"text":"I -- I cannot say it.","start":1378.229,"stop":1379.948,"duration":1.72},{"text":"The one I have in mind, the one that I recall seeing just requires him to be there when he's called for deportation.","start":1379.948,"stop":1388.767,"duration":8.82},{"text":"Now, under the supervisory agreement, Your Honors, we always respond, we always come in.","start":1388.767,"stop":1395.506,"duration":6.74},{"text":"The immigration officer says, \"Be at this office at 10 o'clock”, and next Wednesday, we're there.","start":1395.506,"stop":1401.1,"duration":5.59},{"text":"We don't refuse to come in.","start":1401.1,"stop":1402.906,"duration":1.81},{"text":"We don't refuse to do a solitary thing that they want us to do, although, we feel we have a right to.","start":1402.906,"stop":1409.832,"duration":6.93},{"text":"But when we're questioned, we feel we have a right not to answer certain questions.","start":1409.832,"stop":1414.749,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Now, we come in because maybe the Attorney General has a passport.","start":1414.749,"stop":1420.613,"duration":5.86},{"text":"Well, if he has, we've got to submit to him.","start":1420.613,"stop":1423.731,"duration":3.12},{"text":"And we're told to report once a month while we're on parole.","start":1423.731,"stop":1429.316,"duration":5.59},{"text":"We report once a month.","start":1429.316,"stop":1431.964,"duration":2.65},{"text":"We do absolutely nothing --","start":1431.964,"stop":1433.461,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, you -- you used the word parole.","start":1433.461,"stop":1436.693,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"They used the word parole, Your Honor.","start":1436.693,"stop":1438.436,"duration":1.74},{"text":"They call it supervisory parole.","start":1438.436,"stop":1440.366,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Now, I -- I know parole relates to a former imprisonment and one is released on parole but the Attorney General called it supervisory parole.","start":1440.366,"stop":1448.955,"duration":8.59},{"text":"It's incorrect.","start":1448.955,"stop":1450.698,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"Were you questioned more than once?","start":1450.698,"stop":1454.743,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"They may question everytime we come in but they ordinarily set aside two occasions during a period of a year.","start":1454.743,"stop":1463.161,"duration":8.42},{"text":"Every six months if you're called in, you're asked similar questions all over again.","start":1463.161,"stop":1468.566,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And then most of the time, we answer most of the questions if we believe that they are pertinent to the issue, if they believe -- if we believe that the purpose of the question is to know where the party can be found, et cetera, when they are to be deported.","start":1468.566,"stop":1483.849,"duration":15.28},{"text":"Now, another provision in this so-called supervisory parole agreement is that the person shall not travel beyond 50 miles from Chicago.","start":1483.849,"stop":1492.985,"duration":9.14},{"text":"It's an absurd limitation in our opinion but we just don't do it without getting permission as a matter of fact.","start":1492.985,"stop":1499.739,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are these -- may I ask, are these conditions standardized or are they individualized?","start":1499.739,"stop":1506.217,"duration":6.48},{"text":"In other words --","start":1506.217,"stop":1506.327,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"They are pretty well standardized within a particular district.","start":1506.327,"stop":1510.132,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Now I --","start":1510.132,"stop":1510.323,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I mean are the – are the conditions which are imposed the same in every case that comes up in routine?","start":1510.323,"stop":1514.654,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, I can say that they're practically the same for everyone.","start":1514.654,"stop":1519.802,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they ask him questions about his religion or his church coalitions?","start":1519.802,"stop":1523.963,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I've never had a situation where they asked him what his religion was but they have asked, \"Do you go to church?","start":1523.963,"stop":1531.699,"duration":7.74},{"text":"\"Or words to that effect just like here, \"Do you go to movies at a particular place?","start":1531.699,"stop":1536.302,"duration":4.6},{"text":"\"And always, “What you do with your spare time?","start":1536.302,"stop":1539.653,"duration":3.35},{"text":"How you knew yourself or whom you meet?","start":1539.653,"stop":1541.887,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Where you go?","start":1541.887,"stop":1543.302,"duration":1.41},{"text":"And “What you read very frequently?”","start":1543.302,"stop":1546.692,"duration":3.39},{"text":"Now all of those matters, we say, are protected by the First Amendment.","start":1546.692,"stop":1550.776,"duration":4.08},{"text":"Nobody has the right to inquire and that's why we don't feel that we should answer.","start":1550.776,"stop":1556.963,"duration":6.19},{"text":"Now, when the Attorney General is given the right to say to us that we maybe indicted and maybe penalized with the year out of our lives in $1000 for a refusal to give information as to nationality, circumstances, habits, associations and activities and such other information whether or not related to the foregoing as the Attorney General may deem fit and proper.","start":1556.963,"stop":1583.283,"duration":26.32},{"text":"What is the test to which we're entitled in order to determine in advance whether or not we are subject to $1000 penalty?","start":1583.283,"stop":1592.705,"duration":9.42},{"text":"There's no test of any kind here.","start":1592.705,"stop":1595.876,"duration":3.17},{"text":"It's a situation where the section of the statute determines it and not the indictment itself.","start":1595.876,"stop":1605.876,"duration":10},{"text":"And if the statute or the section of the statute is so vague as not to give proper notice, then the statute and everything else in relation to it must fall.","start":1605.876,"stop":1616.594,"duration":10.72},{"text":"There just isn't any question about it, the Lanzetta case which this Court decided, the Cardiff case which this Court decided fairly recently a number of other cases together.","start":1616.594,"stop":1627.604,"duration":11.01},{"text":"That of course, is so elementary that I don't want to take the court's time about it.","start":1627.604,"stop":1632.203,"duration":4.6},{"text":"But how are we to determine anything?","start":1632.203,"stop":1634.214,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Now, I should say through Your Honors too that in St. Louis, the Zedner case is gradually coming up this way.","start":1634.214,"stop":1643.304,"duration":9.09},{"text":"The Zedner case was a civil proceeding in which it was attempted to enjoin the Attorney General from restricting people as to their movements from requiring them to report at certain times, et cetera.","start":1643.304,"stop":1656.354,"duration":13.05},{"text":"And the Court, it was a three-judge Court, ruled as to several of these restrictions that they were improper.","start":1656.354,"stop":1665.275,"duration":8.92},{"text":"And the Government has appealed from that and Mrs. Zedner herself has also entered a cross-appeal in relation to it.","start":1665.275,"stop":1676.242,"duration":10.97},{"text":"But in that situation, there isn't so very much danger.","start":1676.242,"stop":1679.66,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Why?","start":1679.66,"stop":1680.099,"duration":0.44},{"text":"Because it's just a civil proceeding and it may be determined favorably to the petitioner or may not but at least there's no question about the person's liberty being lost to him.","start":1680.099,"stop":1695.57,"duration":15.47},{"text":"Here, we have a working man who earns $72 or $82 a week with a family of five, who has to put up a $4000 bond on this indictment, who had to engage counsel to represent him and counsels here and it has been placed through all of these expense and great insecurity and great inconvenience because of a statute which, on its face to me at least, is strangely vague and strangely lacking insufficient notice to the defendant for him to know what is required of him.","start":1695.57,"stop":1737.816,"duration":42.25},{"text":"It's a new crime which Congress tried to create.","start":1737.816,"stop":1742.633,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Nothing like this has ever been before this Court before because the law was only enacted in 1950, I believe, and it's a case of first impression, I -- I make them as far as this Court is concerned.","start":1742.633,"stop":1756.543,"duration":13.91},{"text":"Now, I have briefly covered what I feel is relevant under the First Amendment.","start":1756.543,"stop":1767.556,"duration":11.01},{"text":"What we read, whom we see, where we go, what we talk about are things which may not be revealed under circumstances such as this.","start":1767.556,"stop":1780.935,"duration":13.38},{"text":"Take a situation where a person is asked or is requested to testify either before a grand jury or before a court and refuses for some reasons.","start":1780.935,"stop":1791.978,"duration":11.04},{"text":"He may be held in contempt, but most of the time, he is given an opportunity to purge himself of that contempt by saying that he will testify and by so testifying.","start":1791.978,"stop":1804.171,"duration":12.19},{"text":"In this situation, we have nothing, no opening left to the defendant at all.","start":1804.171,"stop":1811.143,"duration":6.97},{"text":"He says he will not testify.","start":1811.143,"stop":1813.242,"duration":2.1},{"text":"There is no possibility of review.","start":1813.242,"stop":1815.274,"duration":2.03},{"text":"There's nobody in the immigration service who has a right to review this situation, merely because some subordinate, sometimes unjustified, I believe, in calling him an under length.","start":1815.274,"stop":1827.564,"duration":12.29},{"text":"Some person asks some questions which cannot, by any stretch of the imagination, be regarded as pertinent.","start":1827.564,"stop":1835.576,"duration":8.01},{"text":"We are immediately subject to indictment.","start":1835.576,"stop":1840.054,"duration":4.48},{"text":"That of itself, I think, ought to be a sufficient consideration for a court in relation to the right of the Attorney General to require a person to testify under those circumstances.","start":1840.054,"stop":1854.793,"duration":14.74},{"text":"I've already shown in relation to other situations.","start":1854.793,"stop":1862.73,"duration":7.94},{"text":"May I call the attention to the fact of testifying before congressional committee?","start":1862.73,"stop":1868.959,"duration":6.23},{"text":"There you have the protection by the law itself which says we are required to testify to those things which are pertinent to the matter which the Committee is investigating.","start":1868.959,"stop":1879.837,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Here, there is nothing at all, not only is they have nothing to say it's pertinent, but the breadth given to the Attorney General is absolutely without any scope at all.","start":1879.837,"stop":1891.852,"duration":12.02},{"text":"He can go as far as he likes and the only way you can test it is to have yourself indicted.","start":1891.852,"stop":1901.737,"duration":9.88},{"text":"One of the questions which I think is of serious import here is the manner of the procedure or the method -- matter of procedure.","start":1901.737,"stop":1912.438,"duration":10.7},{"text":"The question was raised somewhat in the case of the United States versus Spector.","start":1912.438,"stop":1920.481,"duration":8.04},{"text":"There -- there was involved, if the Court please, the question of proceeding on an indictment without proof of the tax leading up to the situation except that of an administrative order of the immigration service.","start":1920.481,"stop":1940.979,"duration":20.5},{"text":"In that particular case, it was said that if that question had been raised, it might have been considered but it wasn't raised there.","start":1940.979,"stop":1949.311,"duration":8.33},{"text":"And therefore, we are asking to have a right to raise it here and that does constitute a constitutional issue or one of the constitutional issues, what have we here.","start":1949.311,"stop":1960.991,"duration":11.68},{"text":"On -- an order of deportation entered by an administrative agency without really the protections of the Administrative Procedures Act, even though there is a review by the Board of Immigration Appeals, an order of deportation so entered becomes the basis for a criminal proceeding.","start":1960.991,"stop":1989.957,"duration":28.97},{"text":"It's contrary in my opinion to the constitutional guarantee to have a right to face your witnesses.","start":1989.957,"stop":1997.852,"duration":7.89},{"text":"You have a right to cross-examine your witnesses.","start":1997.852,"stop":2001.513,"duration":3.66},{"text":"You have a right to subpoena them.","start":2001.513,"stop":2004.062,"duration":2.55},{"text":"Under this proposal, a mere order of an administrative agency without more forms the basis of a criminal proceeding.","start":2004.062,"stop":2018.236,"duration":14.17},{"text":"Now, I'm aware of the Yakus case and I'm aware of the Cox case and some of the other selective servicemen's cases which say that I'm an order of a draft court, a criminal indictment can be brought here, all you have to do is to introduce the order of the draft court to justify such a proceeding.","start":2018.236,"stop":2037.964,"duration":19.73},{"text":"But, Your Honors, there's a great distinction again because take, for instance, the Yakus case, that had to do with rates during the war emergency.","start":2037.964,"stop":2050.389,"duration":12.43},{"text":"It was a strong opinion written by the majority with a strong dissent as well.","start":2050.389,"stop":2057.768,"duration":7.38},{"text":"But in that particular situation, the defendants, are those who were indicted, did not avail themselves of the right of review under the emergency Court of Appeals and that was one of the reasons before the fact that the Court held that under such a situation an indictment could be proceeded upon.","start":2057.768,"stop":2078.514,"duration":20.75},{"text":"Now, the selective service cases are so totally different from this sort of a situation because there, every possible protective device by way of review is thrown about a candidate for the draft, so that he has an opportunity at various stages of the proceedings to show why he should not be drafted if he wants to or to have his situation reviewed so that he doesn't come into a court in this kind of a situation totally liking of and totally naked as to any protection to which he might be entitled to.","start":2078.514,"stop":2118.057,"duration":39.54},{"text":"A person is indicted for robbery, for any crime at all and everybody who is a witness or who can be a witness must come in to testify.","start":2118.057,"stop":2131.276,"duration":13.22},{"text":"In this sort of a proceeding, all of the facts leading up to the order of deportation of which are gathered together in really a quite informal way are reduced to an order and that order that mere slip of paper constitutes the witnesses to the right of the Government to deport.","start":2131.276,"stop":2154.334,"duration":23.06},{"text":"And on the basis of that mere slip of paper, the Government may proceed on this kind of indictment.","start":2154.334,"stop":2160.793,"duration":6.46},{"text":"I think that's definitely contrary to any kind of Anglo-Saxon criminal jurisprudence because it definitely deprives a person of the right to face his accusers.","start":2160.793,"stop":2174.216,"duration":13.42},{"text":"And there's nothing we can do about it.","start":2174.216,"stop":2176.977,"duration":2.76},{"text":"That matter has not been disposed of by this Honorable Court and I sincerely hope that it might have consideration because it -- it's permissible in this kind of a situation.","start":2176.977,"stop":2190.483,"duration":13.51},{"text":"Other situations will develop where it will also be permissible.","start":2190.483,"stop":2194.425,"duration":3.94},{"text":"And on that way by gradual process, those rights which we consider as belonging to us under the constitutional authority are gradually be eliminated.","start":2194.425,"stop":2212.612,"duration":18.19},{"text":"I have touched briefly on the right of an individual not to have his right of locomotion interfered with as it is in this kind of a situation under this kind of a parole agreement.","start":2212.612,"stop":2228.659,"duration":16.05},{"text":"And I think freedom to which a person is entitled to and an alien has the same rights under the Constitution as a native and that too is elementary and I shouldn't take time to say it under that kind of a situation, an alien who is resident here now merely because the Attorney General can't find the place to send him.","start":2228.659,"stop":2251.36,"duration":22.7},{"text":"He should not be restricted in any way at all in his convict except to report for deportation when it is necessary or when it becomes possible to deport him.","start":2251.36,"stop":2262.447,"duration":11.09},{"text":"To do anything else is to punish him for being an alien because we don't punish other people who are not aliens in relation to this kind of a situation.","start":2262.447,"stop":2274.192,"duration":11.74},{"text":"And there's authority, I think, for the position I take and the authority that's cited in the brief.","start":2274.192,"stop":2280.622,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Another matter which occurs to me in connection with that situation is whether or not the Attorney General has a right to any of this at all under the Tenth Amendment because out of the Tenth Amendment, a department of the Government or an official of the Government only has those rights which are proper and necessary to carry out whatever other rights he has.","start":2280.622,"stop":2305.458,"duration":24.84},{"text":"Now, what right has the Attorney General here other than to deport this individual?","start":2305.458,"stop":2312.631,"duration":7.17},{"text":"He has none at all.","start":2312.631,"stop":2315.185,"duration":2.55},{"text":"Supervision, if you call it that, only consists, in my humble opinion, of knowing where he is, so he may be deported.","start":2315.185,"stop":2324.586,"duration":9.4},{"text":"But on the question of supervision and making him behave in doing the right things after his ordered deported, you have the laws of 48 countries, the 48 states which determined what his conduct should be.","start":2324.586,"stop":2337.453,"duration":12.87},{"text":"You have the laws of the Federal Government which determine what his conduct should be.","start":2337.453,"stop":2343.192,"duration":5.74},{"text":"It's not a crime to go to a meeting, unless it'd be a conspiratorial meeting.","start":2343.192,"stop":2349.458,"duration":6.27},{"text":"It's not a time to read or to do any of the other things mentioned here or to go through moving pictures.","start":2349.458,"stop":2354.911,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Hart, why was he deported?","start":2354.911,"stop":2357.668,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- it is not part of the record essentially but he was ordered deported because at one time and not presently, it was said at a hearing, where he was not represented by a counsel, that he had been a member of the Communist Party.","start":2357.668,"stop":2374.455,"duration":16.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that a crime at that time?","start":2374.455,"stop":2376.059,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not a crime at that time.","start":2376.059,"stop":2378.465,"duration":2.41},{"text":"I don't know if it's a crime now, Your Honor.","start":2378.465,"stop":2381.568,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Now --","start":2381.568,"stop":2381.745,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, before you conclude your argument, well you deal with the Carlson case and how you distinguish that?","start":2381.745,"stop":2387.238,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2387.238,"stop":2389.426,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The Carlson case is distinguished by me in only this way that the burden of that case is what rights the Attorney General has in relation to a deportee or prospective deportee for a period of six months subsequent to the order of deportation and not beyond that.","start":2389.426,"stop":2412.02,"duration":22.59},{"text":"Now, the Carlson case arose because a person was denied bail by the Court and by the Attorney General during that six-month period.","start":2412.02,"stop":2423.291,"duration":11.27},{"text":"The case holds that the Attorney General has not an untrammeled right to hold without that that his discretion is subject to review.","start":2423.291,"stop":2434.705,"duration":11.41},{"text":"And that particular feature of the Carlson case is also reviewed by Mr. Justice Clark in the Mezei case where he says that when they hold that the Attorney General may hold for a short period of time for the purpose of affecting deportation but it doesn't go any further than that.","start":2434.705,"stop":2463.529,"duration":28.82},{"text":"Now, the law at the present time is this that if he cannot affect deportation within six months, he's got to release the deportee.","start":2463.529,"stop":2471.94,"duration":8.41},{"text":"And he has to return his bail to him.","start":2471.94,"stop":2474.466,"duration":2.53},{"text":"Now, is the man a better man after six months?","start":2474.466,"stop":2478.514,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Is he a worst man after six months?","start":2478.514,"stop":2480.944,"duration":2.43},{"text":"It's simply the question of what is -- of what the law provides and what is reasonable under the law.","start":2480.944,"stop":2488.087,"duration":7.14},{"text":"The Carlson case, I say, relates only to the first six months subsequent to the order of deportation.","start":2488.087,"stop":2495.522,"duration":7.43},{"text":"And thereafter, it has no bearing except that it says the Attorney General has certain rights which are reviewable.","start":2495.522,"stop":2502.348,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the language in the Carlson case that the Government relies on, as I understand it, is that in fixing bail during that preview for -- or the pre-six month period, they can -- the judge can take into account among other things the fact during the national security which would seem to have no relationship to the availability of the man as a deportee.","start":2502.348,"stop":2531.647,"duration":29.3},{"text":"And it's that language that I would suppose that you – you wanted to deal with.","start":2531.647,"stop":2538.597,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, if Your Honor please, that that is the proximity of the language of the Court in that particular case.","start":2538.597,"stop":2546.579,"duration":7.98},{"text":"But I think you have to view it as limited by the six-month period.","start":2546.579,"stop":2551.855,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And it doesn't have it after the six months?","start":2551.855,"stop":2554.756,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say he does not have it after the six months because he cannot hold without bail after the six months.","start":2554.756,"stop":2561.799,"duration":7.04},{"text":"And to -- pardon?","start":2561.799,"stop":2563.979,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"You would say then you couldn't supervise to the same extent that include before, although we can't with the -- he can't go to jail but can he supervise?","start":2563.979,"stop":2574.558,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that he can only do those things which are necessary and proper under the law to carry out his right.","start":2574.558,"stop":2581.943,"duration":7.39},{"text":"And what is his right, just to deport and nothing else.","start":2581.943,"stop":2586.136,"duration":4.19},{"text":"And he has no right to supervise his conduct.","start":2586.136,"stop":2588.565,"duration":2.43},{"text":"He has no right to say where he -- what meetings he may attend, whether he may make public speeches, whether he may do anything else at all which is a lawful effort on his part, any more than the Attorney General can tell anybody else, a citizen, a national of whether he may do those things.","start":2588.565,"stop":2608.695,"duration":20.13}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And during the six months, the -- the responsibility empowering the Attorney General to supervise availability and security, but after the six month, just availability, is that your position?","start":2608.695,"stop":2619.592,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"If that is the position I take, if the Court please.","start":2619.592,"stop":2622.217,"duration":2.63},{"text":"And I think it's a reasonable position because he has been denied the right to physically supervise him after the six-month period.","start":2622.217,"stop":2632.341,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Certainly, if you're going to talk about supervision holding in custody is perhaps the most secured kind of security, the most secured kind of supervision.","start":2632.341,"stop":2641.659,"duration":9.32},{"text":"But he is denied that right after that.","start":2641.659,"stop":2644.271,"duration":2.61},{"text":"Now, what right has he after the six months?","start":2644.271,"stop":2647.616,"duration":3.34},{"text":"It has been taken away from him the right to hold in prison.","start":2647.616,"stop":2652.404,"duration":4.79},{"text":"But you have not taken away from him the right to deport.","start":2652.404,"stop":2656.792,"duration":4.39},{"text":"That is the only right, that's the naked right, that is left and he has a right to know where the person can be found.","start":2656.792,"stop":2663.064,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"And the Government interest and the public interest is precisely the same -- at the same month, this isn't after six months, isn't it?","start":2663.064,"stop":2672.608,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I could say in answer to that that the Government's interest might be the same but the Government's interest may not be so expressed or they may not be able to exercise.","start":2672.608,"stop":2688.034,"duration":15.43},{"text":"In other words, I mean that this, if the Court please, the mere fact that Congress has said that we're worried about the situation and that we're going to do something about it doesn't give Congress the right to do it.","start":2688.034,"stop":2699.334,"duration":11.3},{"text":"They may only legislate in relation to those things about which they have been given a right.","start":2699.334,"stop":2704.861,"duration":5.53},{"text":"Now, if they haven't been given the right to legislate here as they seem to indicate, the mere intention that they had or the mere desire that they had to do certain things is not justified by the law no matter how much they write it, no matter how much they declare it in the law.","start":2704.861,"stop":2721.713,"duration":16.85},{"text":"That doesn't give them the right to do it.","start":2721.713,"stop":2724.843,"duration":3.13},{"text":"That's why I say, they only have a right to do that which is necessarily improper to carry out the right to deport.","start":2724.843,"stop":2732.948,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"You think that -- you -- you accept Carlson for the preposition that even though the Attorney General says, \"I find there is no security risk in this manner.","start":2732.948,"stop":2745.369,"duration":12.42},{"text":"No danger of you not showing up in the deportation, and nevertheless, in the interest of national security, I'm going to lock them up.","start":2745.369,"stop":2751.436,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Do you accept Carlson for that?","start":2751.436,"stop":2752.945,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, I regretfully say I do not accept Carlson.","start":2752.945,"stop":2756.755,"duration":3.81},{"text":"I accepted as a lawyer because that's the law today.","start":2756.755,"stop":2759.913,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you accept him for that, then you got some trouble in this case I think, but --","start":2759.913,"stop":2764.77,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That maybe -- nevertheless, if the Court please, this Court has acted according through its lights and we'll continue to do so.","start":2764.77,"stop":2774.49,"duration":9.72},{"text":"And since Carlson, I'd say, only relates to the first six-month period and since I also say that the other things that the Attorney General endeavoring to do, he is not authorized to do, I personally, if you don't know inconsistency there.For instance, another thing that the Carlson case said was that they had a right to hold without bail.","start":2774.49,"stop":2800.266,"duration":25.78},{"text":"Now, it's my personal notion that under our kind of law, you had no right to hold without bail except under certain specific situations, but the Court disagrees with me and I accept it as an officer of the Court.","start":2800.266,"stop":2817.51,"duration":17.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say Carlson stands for the proposition that the Attorney General can supervise a person on a ground that he might be a (Inaudible)","start":2817.51,"stop":2832.887,"duration":15.38}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, the Carlson case says that they may hold that the Attorney General may hold without bail --","start":2832.887,"stop":2838.619,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2838.619,"stop":2838.73,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for six months.","start":2838.73,"stop":2839.446,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where does it follow?","start":2839.446,"stop":2840.282,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Our proposition that --","start":2840.282,"stop":2841.808,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that is true, does it follow that because he can hold a man further without bail, he refused to accept this case that he could turn him loose later under an order if he say he had to be out and then he could then do anything you please to him and connects him with supervision.","start":2841.808,"stop":2858.501,"duration":16.69},{"text":"If he is out, the basis of this was, as I understand what you say that he could hold him in jail on the ground that he might be -- name this person, he might infiltrate something.","start":2858.501,"stop":2871.204,"duration":12.7},{"text":"But here, it's been held that the statute provides that he is let out.","start":2871.204,"stop":2877.066,"duration":5.86},{"text":"Why does Carlson left?","start":2877.066,"stop":2878.535,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Why does it follow Carlson that having been decided that he's going to be let out that he used to be under the -- supervision and have to report everyday at two or three or four and that's all the question there is.","start":2878.535,"stop":2893.404,"duration":14.87},{"text":"Where --","start":2893.404,"stop":2893.407,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"When I say --","start":2893.407,"stop":2893.681,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- does it follow?","start":2893.681,"stop":2894.336,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"On the Carlson.","start":2894.336,"stop":2895.679,"duration":1.34},{"text":"What I say, Mr. Justice Black, is that I personally cannot accept Carlson as being correct.","start":2895.679,"stop":2901.144,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose you accept it as correct, does it follow that --","start":2901.144,"stop":2905.27,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it does not.","start":2905.27,"stop":2905.616,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it doesn't have anything to do with this period after the six months --","start":2905.616,"stop":2908.745,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly not.","start":2908.745,"stop":2909.238,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- when the Congress has said, he can be turned down.","start":2909.238,"stop":2911.458,"duration":2.22},{"text":"He must be turned down.","start":2911.458,"stop":2914.059,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it should not be applicable to this kind of a situation.","start":2914.059,"stop":2917.043,"duration":2.98},{"text":"That's where I draw attention to the fact that it's only applicable during the six-month period and not beyond that.","start":2917.043,"stop":2922.02,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's judge -- this is a good thing that Judge Sullivan like.","start":2922.02,"stop":2927.022,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is -- what I'm saying is in relation to the Carlson case itself.","start":2927.022,"stop":2935.94,"duration":8.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about the Carlson case but that's the heart of Judge Sullivan added to, namely, since this statute, that's the (Inaudible) since he cannot be detained after six month but he is still deportable, that warrant is still outstanding, the inquiries must be directed towards securing the enforceability of what is still an outstanding legal order.","start":2935.94,"stop":2967.901,"duration":31.96}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2967.901,"stop":2968.403,"duration":0.5},{"text":"I think in effect that's what Judge Sullivan said.","start":2968.403,"stop":2971.352,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And therefore, he says, \"If questions are to be asked, they have to relate to the man's availability for deportation.”","start":2971.352,"stop":2978.597,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and that's the line you took in answering 70 and not over 20 roughly speaking.","start":2978.597,"stop":2983.611,"duration":5.01},{"text":"I don't mean to stop you or anything, but I mean that's -- you acted on that distinction.","start":2983.611,"stop":2988.401,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Is that right?","start":2988.401,"stop":2990.061,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"I acted not precisely on that.","start":2990.061,"stop":2993.478,"duration":3.42},{"text":"I acted on this but I knew that I could take the Fifth as far as he was concerned.","start":2993.478,"stop":3000.598,"duration":7.12},{"text":"I didn't feel that --","start":3000.598,"stop":3001.743,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's like a medicine now because they have to take the Fifth.","start":3001.743,"stop":3005.273,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3005.273,"stop":3005.73,"duration":0.46},{"text":"That's how they talk about it, Your Honor.","start":3005.73,"stop":3007.008,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know they talk about that and why we must talk about it that way.","start":3007.008,"stop":3009.643,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3009.643,"stop":3011.012,"duration":1.37},{"text":"I could have advised him to plead the Fifth Amendment.","start":3011.012,"stop":3017.249,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Personally, I doubt if he would have taken my advice because as a man of integrity, he felt that he have to answer some questions.","start":3017.249,"stop":3027.081,"duration":9.83},{"text":"He was not required to answer other questions and he didn't want to indulge in any subterfuge at all.","start":3027.081,"stop":3033.697,"duration":6.62},{"text":"And therefore, we drew the line as to that which is pertinent.","start":3033.697,"stop":3036.603,"duration":2.91},{"text":"I've always called it pertinency, Judge Sullivan has called it relevancy --","start":3036.603,"stop":3040.318,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3040.318,"stop":3040.712,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and I don't think they are much the same thing and that's right.","start":3040.712,"stop":3044.119,"duration":3.41},{"text":"And I've also taken the further proposition that there are certain issues which the Attorney General had no right to go into and therefore, they were not pertinent to it.","start":3044.119,"stop":3058.721,"duration":14.6},{"text":"Now, if Your Honors, I think I have practically exhausted my time and I could use more but I -- I don't want to tire the Court.","start":3058.721,"stop":3074.968,"duration":16.25},{"text":"It -- it seems to me that there are situations where a court can constructively and properly take the view that a government or rather a legislature does go beyond the powers which it has and it seems to me very -- when I ran across Thomas Jefferson's letter to James Madison in which he refers to the tyranny of legislatures as being the formidable dread at present and it will be for many years.","start":3074.968,"stop":3108.33,"duration":33.36},{"text":"I found it just about at the time I was writing this brief and I think it is --","start":3108.33,"stop":3112.526,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If he had learned on that subject, didn't he?","start":3112.526,"stop":3115.831,"duration":3.31},{"text":"He thought this Court was the great tyranny.","start":3115.831,"stop":3118.015,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Pearl M. Hart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't know but I feel this that certainly Judge Sullivan's opinion, I think, there is great justification in accepting in the situation.","start":3118.015,"stop":3137.318,"duration":19.3},{"text":"I think there's logic there and I think there is reason and I think there is everything else which requires an affirmation there.","start":3137.318,"stop":3146.181,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Some of us who are so greatly interested in matters of the constitutional law would be very grateful if the Court found it possible to consider other phases which I have called your attention.","start":3146.181,"stop":3160.325,"duration":14.14},{"text":"Thank you so much.","start":3160.325,"stop":3163.661,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis.","start":3163.661,"stop":3165.51,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and the Court please.","start":3165.51,"stop":3169.813,"duration":4.3},{"text":"One matter of clarification, Ms. Hart spoke of a --","start":3169.813,"stop":3174.19,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3174.19,"stop":3174.781,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- supervision agreement.","start":3174.781,"stop":3177.773,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I think what she has in mind is that at the time a supervisory order is issued, it is presented to the alien for him to acknowledge that he has read and understood it and that he understands what failure to comply with the terms of the order will -- will result here.","start":3177.773,"stop":3199.473,"duration":21.7},{"text":"As a matter of fact on page 31 of the record at the end of this supervisory order, there is the place for the signature of the alien to show that he has received and served with the copy of this supervisory order.","start":3199.473,"stop":3212.349,"duration":12.88},{"text":"In this case, the alien refused to sign it and so there was a note that it was read to him instead of his having agreed that he had read it.","start":3212.349,"stop":3224.02,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, the most two important, I'm just curious, do you have any idea why they dropped out that question on the Chicago Tribune?","start":3224.02,"stop":3231.934,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Why they dropped it out of the indictment?","start":3231.934,"stop":3233.374,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3233.374,"stop":3235.035,"duration":1.66},{"text":"It seems to be the argument --","start":3235.035,"stop":3235.665,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that --","start":3235.665,"stop":3235.779,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3235.779,"stop":3236.431,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it may well confront that it wasn't immaterial to the -- that the question wasn't immaterial.","start":3236.431,"stop":3241.482,"duration":5.05},{"text":"I don't know.","start":3241.482,"stop":3242.851,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"First Amendment probably.","start":3242.851,"stop":3244.369,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":3244.369,"stop":3244.822,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"First Amendment probably.","start":3244.822,"stop":3246.017,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It may have been so.","start":3246.017,"stop":3247.254,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Our deference to Chicago Tribune, its great sponsorship of that Amendment.","start":3247.254,"stop":3251.267,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have no information why they dropped it.","start":3251.267,"stop":3253.586,"duration":2.32},{"text":"I -- I'm glad they did drop it.","start":3253.586,"stop":3255.044,"duration":1.46},{"text":"I -- I wouldn't like it.","start":3255.044,"stop":3257.061,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I should think the vast of the United States Attorney who prosecuted this indictment if he ever has to the trial, I'd be glad they drop it too.","start":3257.061,"stop":3268.101,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the basic question on constitutionality on this question is whether or not this type of supervision is considered by the Court to be a reasonable -- a reasonable device to meet the situation which existed.","start":3268.101,"stop":3288.316,"duration":20.21},{"text":"There's no question that there was a trouble in situation with 4000 aliens who had been -- who would had been ordered deported and couldn't be deported and we're under no restrictions or whatsoever as to that conduct.","start":3288.316,"stop":3302.582,"duration":14.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the total under the six months rule as dictated?","start":3302.582,"stop":3305.848,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, that was the total at the time of the enactment.","start":3305.848,"stop":3308.681,"duration":2.83},{"text":"It's about the same day though.","start":3308.681,"stop":3312.272,"duration":3.59},{"text":"This figure of aliens who are subject to supervision today is 4356.","start":3312.272,"stop":3319.487,"duration":7.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and these are all under the six months rule, is that it?","start":3319.487,"stop":3322.134,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That was, of all -- the supervisory orders cannot be issued.","start":3322.134,"stop":3325.021,"duration":2.89},{"text":"That's right.","start":3325.021,"stop":3325.555,"duration":0.53},{"text":"That's -- this isn't under any bond.","start":3325.555,"stop":3327.312,"duration":1.76},{"text":"This is under the --","start":3327.312,"stop":3327.438,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I understand it.","start":3327.438,"stop":3328.167,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- six-month rule.","start":3328.167,"stop":3328.953,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And on the -- what I meant the six months rule because they belong to countries that we find it difficult to get them.","start":3328.953,"stop":3337.424,"duration":8.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They haven't been -- for one reason or another, they had not been able to deport them.","start":3337.424,"stop":3341.291,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Including state, but isn't the chief reasoned that they belong to?","start":3341.291,"stop":3345.6,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that is right.","start":3345.6,"stop":3346.227,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then the stateless ones, they are good many or some stateless ones --","start":3346.227,"stop":3350.042,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":3350.042,"stop":3350.053,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- aren't they?","start":3350.053,"stop":3350.804,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There are many -- there are many problems out in this case.","start":3350.804,"stop":3353.413,"duration":2.61},{"text":"It's find from certain that we would kind of to find that the -- the immigration service can't find a place to deport him to because they're just delays.","start":3353.413,"stop":3360.753,"duration":7.34},{"text":"They get -- no, he has indicated, the first place is the place that the alien indicates and he has indicated Yugoslavia.","start":3360.753,"stop":3367.452,"duration":6.7},{"text":"And all that has happened is on the record because they can't get any answer from Yugoslavia whether they have taken him or not.","start":3367.452,"stop":3373.378,"duration":5.93},{"text":"When they get an answer, by then the statute provides for alternative places to deport him but this is -- this is the cause of the delay.","start":3373.378,"stop":3381.575,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, didn't -- didn't he testify to that he came from the old Austro-Hungarian Empire and where he came from that wasn't clear.","start":3381.575,"stop":3390.028,"duration":8.45},{"text":"Yugoslavia recognized that he was now a Yugoslavian.","start":3390.028,"stop":3394.453,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":3394.453,"stop":3395.133,"duration":0.68},{"text":"He has, however, the right to choose the first place that they deport an alien to --","start":3395.133,"stop":3400.799,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3400.799,"stop":3401.009,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is the place that he chooses.","start":3401.009,"stop":3402.45,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm just wondering if this has sustained what was done here and they -- no one takes them, I take that he is subject to this kind of supervision for the rest of his life, isn't it?","start":3402.45,"stop":3412.497,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No because there are alternative places to deport him.","start":3412.497,"stop":3414.912,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And suppose no one takes him.","start":3414.912,"stop":3416.384,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if no one takes him, why didn't he --","start":3416.384,"stop":3418.884,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He goes through this the rest of his life.","start":3418.884,"stop":3420.49,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is so if it was impossible to deport him to any place.","start":3420.49,"stop":3424.329,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There are these -- these none takings, take Yugoslavia, am I right that -- I don't know how many but I suspect there could be instances, have nothing to do either in determining whether he was or wasn't a part of what it is now Yugoslavia, what it is now Hungary.","start":3424.329,"stop":3444.384,"duration":20.05},{"text":"But it also is part of the general foothold of international relations having nothing to do with the individual, but being -- for reasons of the foreign office notions of different countries saying, \"We just do nothing about this but these are that reasons.\"","start":3444.384,"stop":3458.984,"duration":14.6},{"text":"Isn't that a considerable fashion?","start":3458.984,"stop":3460.607,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is very true but the present -- and the present Immigration Act, the -- the Immigration Nationality Act of 1952 put steps to remedy to this situation to give the Attorney General authority to broaden the countries that he could -- that he could use as a place to -- of haven for this people so that we can hope that the administration under the new Act will cut down on -- on the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3460.607,"stop":3484.781,"duration":24.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) but if -- if an alien -- these are his countries of first choice to get his first choice.","start":3484.781,"stop":3491.793,"duration":7.01},{"text":"Then, the Government tries to get him and admitted there and that may rely under this that the foreign office in Belgrade for reason of having nothing to do with this.","start":3491.793,"stop":3501.494,"duration":9.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3501.494,"stop":3502.572,"duration":1.08},{"text":"But in -- in reasonable time, I'm sure the Government can take that as a denial and go on to the next -- for the next country.","start":3502.572,"stop":3508.365,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, what support does the statute get from the fact that there's been a deportation offer?","start":3508.365,"stop":3515.274,"duration":6.91},{"text":"Why is that necessary?","start":3515.274,"stop":3516.456,"duration":1.18},{"text":"I have gathered from your argument that it's the danger of security division to give authority and that's based on the fact that he used to be incompetent.","start":3516.456,"stop":3528.058,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Why do you need the deportation orders for the statute of that kind?","start":3528.058,"stop":3532.439,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I am not certain that a deportation order would be essential to asking questions.","start":3532.439,"stop":3537.662,"duration":5.22},{"text":"We all -- we have an alien registration law which -- which then authorizes the service to ask many questions of all aliens here whether they are deported or not.","start":3537.662,"stop":3549.896,"duration":12.23},{"text":"I -- my argument, however, was that the supervisory -- the supervisory order on these questions received content from the fact that there has been an order of deportation and the basis for that order.","start":3549.896,"stop":3564.41,"duration":14.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If aliens who have -- they have been ordered deported and be subject to the supervision of government agents, why cannot other aliens?","start":3564.41,"stop":3575.932,"duration":11.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"At the present time, the alien registration law provides for registration of all aliens in this country.","start":3575.932,"stop":3581.917,"duration":5.99},{"text":"It provides the annual report by all aliens in this country.","start":3581.917,"stop":3585.505,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it provide for supervision, the power of the Attorney General --","start":3585.505,"stop":3590.079,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Following that question, no.","start":3590.079,"stop":3590.787,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) asking questions --","start":3590.787,"stop":3592.593,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, except as the annual report form or whatever the annual report form may be.","start":3592.593,"stop":3597.522,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't myself get to see that is -- but maybe -- maybe others can whether there's any much constitutional support added to the statute by --","start":3597.522,"stop":3607.32,"duration":9.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no --","start":3607.32,"stop":3607.633,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- neither because of the deportation --","start":3607.633,"stop":3608.848,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, my argument --","start":3608.848,"stop":3609.12,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3609.12,"stop":3609.926,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- my argument was that the deportation order gave reasonable content to the supervisory order that since this is supplementary to the deportation that there are some reasonable restrictions on the Attorney General as to the nature of this --","start":3609.926,"stop":3624.018,"duration":14.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I think that they brought an offer to this supported by the statute itself.","start":3624.018,"stop":3629.709,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And my basis for saying that is that in Carlson against Landon, then the -- the thought of the -- the nature of the deportation proceeding had a relation to the Attorney General's authority to -- to confine the aliens.","start":3629.709,"stop":3644.193,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it doesn't follow that we have to decide now what -- how a supervision one have over aliens which the policy of this country allows whom the policy of his country allows to remain here, I suppose we still have what, two or three million aliens?","start":3644.193,"stop":3661.797,"duration":17.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":3661.797,"stop":3662.378,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"More than that?","start":3662.378,"stop":3663.585,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I wasn't suggesting this Court to pass upon the constitutionality of the Alien Registration Act.","start":3663.585,"stop":3668.12,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't they still about being in the Navy?","start":3668.12,"stop":3669.843,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't know the numbers.","start":3669.843,"stop":3671.203,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And again, these people who are ready to be deported and legislation is completely related to that group of people.","start":3671.203,"stop":3680.183,"duration":8.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the special legislation with respect to aliens during the war -- under the war power, there are certain circumstances where different regulations seemed to be appropriate.","start":3680.183,"stop":3688.268,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Always not though.","start":3688.268,"stop":3691.135,"duration":2.87}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 28, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13320","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 295, United States of America, Appellant, versus George I. Witkovich.","start":0,"stop":25.143,"duration":25.14},{"text":"Mr. Davis.","start":25.143,"stop":27.272,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":27.272,"stop":35.916,"duration":8.64},{"text":"The issue in this case is whether with respect to an alien who has been ordered deported but whose deportation has not been accomplished, the Government may exercise supervision, not only to insure his availability for deportation but also to prevent a continuation of the type of conduct which led to the order for deportation.","start":35.916,"stop":71.572,"duration":35.66},{"text":"In the present case, Mr. George I. Witkovich, the alien, was indicted for refusing to answer certain questions which would put to him by the Immigration Service.","start":71.572,"stop":85.346,"duration":13.77},{"text":"He had earlier been ordered deported and attempts had been made to remove him to Yugoslavia.","start":85.346,"stop":94.562,"duration":9.22},{"text":"However, more than six months have elapsed since the order of deportation and the deportation had not been accomplished.","start":94.562,"stop":105.257,"duration":10.7},{"text":"Meanwhile, an order of supervision had been served on him requiring him -- requiring him to report monthly to the Immigration Service, not to change his residence without giving notice and not to engage in Communist activities or to associate with Communists.","start":105.257,"stop":129.91,"duration":24.65},{"text":"The Immigration Act provides that an alien subject to a supervisory order shall give information under oath when requested with respect to his nationality, his habits, circumstances, his associates and his activities, such of the matters as the Attorney General may deem fit and proper.","start":129.91,"stop":155.259,"duration":25.35},{"text":"In an attempt to find out whether Mr. Witkovich was continuing his activities with the Communists, an -- an investigator for the Immigration Service asked him a serious -- series of questions dealing with his associations and his activities.","start":155.259,"stop":174.702,"duration":19.44},{"text":"And these he declined to answer, not claiming -- specifically, not claiming the protection of the Fifth Amendment.","start":174.702,"stop":183.538,"duration":8.84},{"text":"Now under the Act, it is a crime to refuse to answer such questions if these were proper questions.","start":183.538,"stop":192.526,"duration":8.99},{"text":"Mr. Witkovich was indicted.","start":192.526,"stop":195.358,"duration":2.83},{"text":"The District Court dismissed the indictment on the ground that the statute must be construed to permit questions which deal solely with the alien's availability for deportation.","start":195.358,"stop":210.519,"duration":15.16},{"text":"And since the questions involved did not deal solely with this question but rather with the question of his activities and associations with the Communist Party that the indictment was dismissed.","start":210.519,"stop":224.052,"duration":13.53},{"text":"And since this -- the dismissal results from a construction of the statute, we are here on direct appeal.","start":224.052,"stop":232.678,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"But they did relate to the cause for which he was ordered deported, is that so?","start":232.678,"stop":237.164,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":237.164,"stop":240.581,"duration":3.42},{"text":"He was deported --","start":240.581,"stop":241.004,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis --","start":241.004,"stop":241.54,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for membership in the Communist Party.","start":241.54,"stop":243.8,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you please advise me -- assume -- assume we're against you on construction.","start":243.8,"stop":252.56,"duration":8.76},{"text":"Can we -- say can we be assuming we could under the criminality of act, shouldn't we reach constitutionality?","start":252.56,"stop":267.746,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":267.746,"stop":269.102,"duration":1.36},{"text":"Since the case is properly before this Court, there's no question that this -- this case comes up properly because it was dismissed on that ground.","start":269.102,"stop":275.177,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- you know that.","start":275.177,"stop":276.586,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But once it is properly -- a proper direct appeal to this Court then the constitutionality of the statute would be -- would be before the Court if the Court decided to -- to exercise its jurisdiction.","start":276.586,"stop":288.079,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And as you're proposing, I mean as a matter of jurisdiction.","start":288.079,"stop":291.476,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":291.476,"stop":292.007,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of jurisdiction.","start":292.007,"stop":293.453,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as a matter of practice too, although I can't cite you cases, but then -- then I'm sure that on this constitutionality has come up frequently in this direct appeals on -- on --","start":293.453,"stop":302.261,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't doubt that.But this is a question that's been wrapping around my head.","start":302.261,"stop":307.62,"duration":5.36},{"text":"It's (Inaudible) whether -- when the court of -- the court below sustained it and it didn't reach -- or rather sustained the statute on his construction and we disagree with his construction.","start":307.62,"stop":325.268,"duration":17.65},{"text":"Should we go then reach a question which he on his construction didn't reach?","start":325.268,"stop":330.493,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":330.493,"stop":332.423,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":332.423,"stop":333.232,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is a different question but --","start":333.232,"stop":334.848,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- like it.","start":334.848,"stop":335.71,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the question would be whether the Court would feel that if the --","start":335.71,"stop":338.022,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- it's a question of -- hold there.","start":338.022,"stop":340.338,"duration":2.32},{"text":"In other words, (B) my second question was, (A), could we, (B), should we, are different questions.","start":340.338,"stop":343.679,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":343.679,"stop":344.688,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer to could we, is I should think --","start":344.688,"stop":346.2,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":346.2,"stop":346.688,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's clear, yes.","start":346.688,"stop":347.986,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And whether you should --","start":347.986,"stop":348.957,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":348.957,"stop":349.063,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is whether or not you feel that it will be --","start":349.063,"stop":350.985,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I just wanted to be sure that I was correct in assuming that jurisdiction --","start":350.985,"stop":356.232,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":356.232,"stop":360.387,"duration":4.15},{"text":"The statute in question is the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1952 and specifically Section 242 (d) which we have read it at pages 2 and 3 of our brief.","start":360.387,"stop":376.363,"duration":15.98},{"text":"The pattern of the Act is that after an alien is arrested for deportation proceedings, the Attorney General may within his discretion keep him in custody for the duration of the proceedings.","start":376.363,"stop":395.52,"duration":19.16},{"text":"This section of the Act -- the Section of the Act which provides this was the section which was before this Court in Carlson against Landon a few years ago where the constitutionality of the detention was upheld and the -- the statute was interpreted as giving the Attorney General authority to retain the alien in custody when it was necessary in the -- for the welfare of the country.","start":395.52,"stop":422.631,"duration":27.11},{"text":"After a final order of deportation has been handed, the Attorney General may still keep the alien in confinement for a period of six months only while he attempts to arrange the details of deportation.","start":422.631,"stop":438.158,"duration":15.53},{"text":"When the six-month period has ended after a period of -- after the final order of deportation, the Attorney General no longer has any discretion to retain the alien in custody.","start":438.158,"stop":452.934,"duration":14.78},{"text":"But under the Section which is now before the Court, the Attorney General is authorized to place the alien under a supervisory order.","start":452.934,"stop":463.287,"duration":10.35},{"text":"And our question is what is the nature of that supervision and is that supervision constitutional?","start":463.287,"stop":470.428,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell me Mr. Davis, was there some particular reason why after the end of six months, he had to stay here?","start":470.428,"stop":476.411,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He hadn't been deported?","start":476.411,"stop":477.78,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":477.78,"stop":481.492,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It very frequently happens in these Communist cases that it's difficult to -- to get permission from the foreign country.","start":481.492,"stop":487.898,"duration":6.41},{"text":"In this case, his country was Yugoslavia.","start":487.898,"stop":491.008,"duration":3.11},{"text":"Application had been made to the consul in -- in Chicago for the proper papers.","start":491.008,"stop":497.611,"duration":6.6},{"text":"They've referred it to Yugoslavia and received no answer.","start":497.611,"stop":500.486,"duration":2.88},{"text":"And whenever there was inquiry made as to what happened, they'd say we haven't heard and that is the status.","start":500.486,"stop":509.121,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, don't these cases often lie in the files of the Immigration Bureau without action on them for a long, long time?","start":509.121,"stop":520.23,"duration":11.11}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Without -- without the -- without the deportation being accomplished Mr. Chief Justice.","start":520.23,"stop":524.248,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":524.248,"stop":525.043,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true.","start":525.043,"stop":525.604,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Without an appeal being taken or anything of that kind?","start":525.604,"stop":529.074,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the alien frequently doesn't challenge the appropriateness of the deportation order until the deportation is imminent because he gains additional time if he -- if while they're arranging for the deportation he doesn't do -- he doesn't challenge it.","start":529.074,"stop":545.598,"duration":16.52},{"text":"He can bring it up on habeas corpus when the time comes to actually deport him.","start":545.598,"stop":549.496,"duration":3.9},{"text":"So, if there are difficulties in arranging for the deportation, he gets the additional time in this country if he doesn't pass the validity of the order until the actual time for deportation comes.","start":549.496,"stop":561.521,"duration":12.02},{"text":"But when you say that they lie dormant in the services' files, I think that -- that shouldn't be -- we shouldn't be -- I shouldn't be construed as -- as saying that the services in attempting to process this file isn't attempting to deport these people.","start":561.521,"stop":577.433,"duration":15.91},{"text":"It's a difficult problem and -- and they haven't finished the -- completed the deportation, but they have been attempting to.","start":577.433,"stop":583.124,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the reason I ask you this, sir, in the state service, we used to get communications from the Bureau of Immigration saying that so and so was ordered deported on a certain day.","start":583.124,"stop":595.674,"duration":12.55},{"text":"It may have been a couple of years before.","start":595.674,"stop":598.722,"duration":3.05},{"text":"And it appears that he's been convicted of a crime in your State.","start":598.722,"stop":604.237,"duration":5.51},{"text":"If he is relieved, if the Governor will grant a pardon or he's relieved of it in any way, it will not be necessary to deport him.","start":604.237,"stop":613.499,"duration":9.26},{"text":"And sometimes we get letters over -- over a long period of time and it -- it wouldn't hardly consist that we've an appeal from the -- from the order of deportation and they just appear to me that there are lot of those cases that -- that just were in limbo and -- and --","start":613.499,"stop":630.663,"duration":17.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that kind of inquiry should come to all promptly.","start":630.663,"stop":633.205,"duration":2.54},{"text":"It may be that there are other steps.","start":633.205,"stop":635.01,"duration":1.8},{"text":"Maybe there'd been applications for discretionary relief to let him stay.","start":635.01,"stop":641.884,"duration":6.87},{"text":"Maybe he didn't -- maybe they waited until the time it became imminent before they asked it.","start":641.884,"stop":646.223,"duration":4.34},{"text":"I -- I --","start":646.223,"stop":646.665,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":646.665,"stop":647.004,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- don't know but that kind of query I should think should come soon after the order of the deportation.","start":647.004,"stop":651.635,"duration":4.63},{"text":"I see no excuse for it being --","start":651.635,"stop":652.915,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":652.915,"stop":653.718,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That very much explain it.","start":653.718,"stop":656.162,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is the practice Mr. Davis, ordinarily to -- to deport him as quickly as possible (Voice Overlap) --","start":656.162,"stop":661.324,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"As possible.","start":661.324,"stop":662.066,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":662.066,"stop":662.557,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The six months, in other words, is set aside to let him wind up his personal affairs.","start":662.557,"stop":667.509,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- well, they don't -- there's no necessity of waiting six months.","start":667.509,"stop":671.317,"duration":3.81},{"text":"He has no right to remain in this country for six months.","start":671.317,"stop":673.447,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I mean I'm -- but the statute does provide for -- well --","start":673.447,"stop":678.766,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean the amount really --","start":678.766,"stop":679.117,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- but if it -- if -- but he may have up to six months to wind up his personal affairs, may he not?","start":679.117,"stop":684.981,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- not his right.","start":684.981,"stop":686.787,"duration":1.81},{"text":"The -- the statute provides -- the Attorney General may keep him in confinement for a period of six months while he's making arrangements to deport him.","start":686.787,"stop":696.194,"duration":9.41},{"text":"But there is no -- there is no right on the alien to remain for six months as soon as the order becomes final.","start":696.194,"stop":702.856,"duration":6.66},{"text":"Then there is the -- the legal right to deport.","start":702.856,"stop":706.468,"duration":3.61},{"text":"I -- I'm not suggesting that the service acts precipitantly in these matters.","start":706.468,"stop":710.943,"duration":4.48},{"text":"I think that -- I'm -- I have no information about it.","start":710.943,"stop":712.952,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm still not quite clear what the six months is for.","start":712.952,"stop":716.292,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The six months is a period when if the Attorney General feels it's necessary to protect the country from a continuation of the activity leading to deportations.","start":716.292,"stop":728.025,"duration":11.73},{"text":"He can protect the country by holding the alien in confinement.","start":728.025,"stop":732.431,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":732.431,"stop":733.887,"duration":1.46},{"text":"It's not -- it's not for the benefit of the alien himself.","start":733.887,"stop":735.942,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not for the benefit of the alien and the six months limitation was put on it because there was a feeling in Congress that there would be constitutional difficulties in holding a man indefinitely if -- when he hasn't been --","start":735.942,"stop":748.201,"duration":12.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So then in effect, he's released but then somewhat like parole --","start":748.201,"stop":751.604,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":751.604,"stop":751.704,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who are under supervision.","start":751.704,"stop":752.907,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":752.907,"stop":753.705,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Until he's finally deported.","start":753.705,"stop":755.195,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":755.195,"stop":757.222,"duration":2.03},{"text":"The background of this provision on supervision is that under the 1917 Act, in cases where aliens had been ordered deported, there was just -- and we -- they haven't been able to accomplish deportation.","start":757.222,"stop":771.711,"duration":14.49},{"text":"There was no control over them or whatsoever.","start":771.711,"stop":773.474,"duration":1.76},{"text":"They -- no one knew where they were and what they were doing.","start":773.474,"stop":776.4,"duration":2.93},{"text":"And meanwhile, there were certain Eastern European countries and some countries in the Far East who were refusing to take back aliens which had been ordered deported from the United States.","start":776.4,"stop":789.939,"duration":13.54},{"text":"As a matter of fact, by 1950, there were some 4000 aliens who have been ordered deported and that the -- the Government was unable to accomplish the deportations.","start":789.939,"stop":801.251,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now tell me, are there instances in which the -- the Attorney General does not confine him but lets him --","start":801.251,"stop":807.484,"duration":6.23}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":807.484,"stop":807.882,"duration":0.4},{"text":"In this case, the -- this -- Mr. Witkovich was -- was -- well, he was released on bail.","start":807.882,"stop":814.245,"duration":6.36},{"text":"A bail was provided and he couldn't make the bail, so before the proceedings, he was actually confined.","start":814.245,"stop":819.19,"duration":4.95},{"text":"After the order, however, he was released on bail.","start":819.19,"stop":823.679,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The -- the Attorney General has the authority in that six months period to confine or to release on such bond as he believes appropriate and the --","start":823.679,"stop":831.525,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But in either case after the six months.","start":831.525,"stop":834.186,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"After the six months, he may not --","start":834.186,"stop":835.361,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":835.361,"stop":836.151,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as supervisory on him.","start":836.151,"stop":838.832,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that last statement?","start":838.832,"stop":839.969,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"After the six months, he has authority to place and make him subject to a supervisory order, this type of order which we have before us now.","start":839.969,"stop":846.447,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It would seem you said something he may not, what may not?","start":846.447,"stop":850.375,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Well, I misheard.","start":850.375,"stop":850.816,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I think that what I've said to Mr. Justice Brennan was that during the six months period, he may not and very frequently -- most frequently does not retain the alien in custody but releases him on bond during that six months period and Mr. Witkovich himself was released (Voice Overlap) --","start":850.816,"stop":867.584,"duration":16.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"After six months, he must.","start":867.584,"stop":869.391,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And after the six months, he must.","start":869.391,"stop":870.731,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He must.","start":870.731,"stop":871.399,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He must.","start":871.399,"stop":871.983,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No doubt about that.","start":871.983,"stop":872.752,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":872.752,"stop":873.751,"duration":1},{"text":"He has no authority to keep him confined after the six months period.","start":873.751,"stop":876.903,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No matter what the alien does.","start":876.903,"stop":879.388,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless, --","start":879.388,"stop":879.437,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean I don't --","start":879.437,"stop":880.122,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- he's convicted of a crime or something.","start":880.122,"stop":881.507,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, (Inaudible)","start":881.507,"stop":882.563,"duration":1.06},{"text":"That's true of people (Inaudible)","start":882.563,"stop":885.66,"duration":3.1},{"text":"But -- but that's I think that's rather crucial a bit but not crucial but it's -- that the heart of the --","start":885.66,"stop":891.007,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":891.007,"stop":891.982,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of case from a part of Judge Sullivan's position, isn't it?","start":891.982,"stop":896.049,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":896.049,"stop":897.62,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the relevancy of the question like you used to describe to the daily worker?","start":897.62,"stop":902.884,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":902.884,"stop":905.102,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"It must be a lot of libraries in --","start":905.102,"stop":906.659,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":906.659,"stop":906.927,"duration":0.27},{"text":"I -- I --","start":906.927,"stop":907.602,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- people (Voice Overlap) --","start":907.602,"stop":908.001,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I would hate to have to defend this case on the basis of that question.","start":908.001,"stop":912.921,"duration":4.92},{"text":"I think the pertinence of it is that in the Communist Party, the -- the members are encouraged, perhaps required to read the Communist literature.","start":912.921,"stop":923.075,"duration":10.15},{"text":"However, I would -- I would be reluctant to have to defend this case on -- on the basis of that particular question because I think you have a very real First Amendment question.","start":923.075,"stop":934.28,"duration":11.2},{"text":"People have the right to print the daily worker.","start":934.28,"stop":937.631,"duration":3.35},{"text":"People have a right to print it.","start":937.631,"stop":938.781,"duration":1.15},{"text":"We shouldn't be -- they shouldn't be prevented from reading it.","start":938.781,"stop":940.222,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the case that --","start":940.222,"stop":941.716,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't think we do rest upon that question.","start":941.716,"stop":943.667,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":943.667,"stop":944.369,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But you must rest upon some question.","start":944.369,"stop":946.06,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":946.06,"stop":946.325,"duration":0.27},{"text":"I'd rest upon the question as to associations and activities.","start":946.325,"stop":949.894,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The question, are you a member of the Communist Party that you associate with so and so, did you associate with so and so?","start":949.894,"stop":957.569,"duration":7.67},{"text":"The questions accept --","start":957.569,"stop":958.07,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That the grounds for his deportation -- or that he is a member?","start":958.07,"stop":961.758,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that -- that he had been a member between certain days, yes.","start":961.758,"stop":965.723,"duration":3.96},{"text":"Not that he -- he may be a member.","start":965.723,"stop":967.633,"duration":1.91},{"text":"There's no indication whether he is or not.","start":967.633,"stop":969.176,"duration":1.54},{"text":"That's what the -- that's what the --","start":969.176,"stop":970.75,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What are the -- what's the relevancy of -- of maybe kind of any movies in the Cinema Annex?","start":970.75,"stop":975.677,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry I don't know what -- on the pertinency of that question is.","start":975.677,"stop":978.605,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you attended any lectures at people's auditorium?","start":978.605,"stop":981.403,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I have no idea what the -- what the significance of that question is.","start":981.403,"stop":984.234,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he address any (Inaudible)","start":984.234,"stop":987.523,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And I don't know that either.","start":987.523,"stop":989.229,"duration":1.71},{"text":"I presume that if the case had gone on for trial, it would have had to be the judgment would have to set aside as to the pertinency of any questions that were asked.","start":989.229,"stop":997.392,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You recognized apparently then there are some limits to the -- despite the broad -- to determine (Inaudible) the statute.","start":997.392,"stop":1005.076,"duration":7.68},{"text":"There are several limits to what the Attorney General can ask under his judgment.","start":1005.076,"stop":1008.719,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's right.","start":1008.719,"stop":1009.494,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what are those limits?","start":1009.494,"stop":1010.934,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they must be consistent with the -- with the object of the -- of the supervision.","start":1010.934,"stop":1015.556,"duration":4.62},{"text":"The -- well, specifically let's put it --","start":1015.556,"stop":1017.747,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It was simply to deport him, isn't it?","start":1017.747,"stop":1019.439,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1019.439,"stop":1019.805,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is to deport him?","start":1019.805,"stop":1021.557,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":1021.557,"stop":1022.319,"duration":0.76},{"text":"Well, I think that the supervision is not only to deport him but our argument here is that Congress intended the Attorney General to have power to inhibit these activities which led to the deportation.","start":1022.319,"stop":1037.525,"duration":15.21},{"text":"Now, in this case, he was deported because it would prove that he had been a voluntary member of the Communist Party from at least 1940 to 1949 and the object of these questions, some of which the pertinence of which I -- I have no idea, but the presumed object of this was to find out whether he was continuing activities in connection with the Communist Party.","start":1037.525,"stop":1061.589,"duration":24.06},{"text":"The order of supervision had ordered that he should cease to --","start":1061.589,"stop":1065.586,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that make him anymore deportable than he already had been found to be?","start":1065.586,"stop":1069.411,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it didn't make him anymore deportable.","start":1069.411,"stop":1071.406,"duration":1.99},{"text":"He was ordered to be deported and could be deported at any time that the arrangements could be made.","start":1071.406,"stop":1076.202,"duration":4.8},{"text":"This -- the -- the real question in here is that whether -- in order to prevent -- well, in the first place, the -- does the -- does the Government have a right to prevent this kind of activities by aliens who were deported?","start":1076.202,"stop":1087.707,"duration":11.51},{"text":"If so, is it appropriate to do it by confining them as is done for the six months period or -- or could have been longer by statute.","start":1087.707,"stop":1097.004,"duration":9.3},{"text":"Or is it appropriate to inhibit this type of activity which Congress believes is improper?","start":1097.004,"stop":1103.358,"duration":6.35},{"text":"Is it proper to inhibit -- inhibited by this type of parole arrangement and requiring reports from the alien?","start":1103.358,"stop":1109.804,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it that your -- that you were here where you conceive the case to be this.","start":1109.804,"stop":1116.552,"duration":6.75},{"text":"There's an outstanding deportation order.","start":1116.552,"stop":1119.283,"duration":2.73},{"text":"The validity of that is not in question now and cannot be considered that the order was not executed for six months for good and sufficient reasons presumably.","start":1119.283,"stop":1131.681,"duration":12.4},{"text":"And then came into operation the provision of the statute that at the end of six months, he must be allowed freedom subject to conditions upon his movement.","start":1131.681,"stop":1146.876,"duration":15.19},{"text":"I'm not now saying how limited they may be.","start":1146.876,"stop":1149.811,"duration":2.93},{"text":"But the Attorney General may impose conditions from letting him in and --","start":1149.811,"stop":1156.157,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1156.157,"stop":1156.29,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- (Inaudible) will that at the end of six months, it would be your own t to detain him.","start":1156.29,"stop":1162.035,"duration":5.75},{"text":"The conditions aren't here.","start":1162.035,"stop":1166.093,"duration":4.06},{"text":"The legality of the specific conditions aren't here in question, are they?","start":1166.093,"stop":1173.249,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the --","start":1173.249,"stop":1174.736,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So are they?","start":1174.736,"stop":1175.422,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they may be.","start":1175.422,"stop":1176.474,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I think that it --","start":1176.474,"stop":1177.487,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me -- let me go step by step.","start":1177.487,"stop":1179.186,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Suppose we first say that assuming the conditions are relevant to the -- the Act of Congress making the provision of what you have at the end of six months, but then the question is not whether a particular question but assuming questions that there be such in this roster of questions.","start":1179.186,"stop":1200.67,"duration":21.48},{"text":"Assuming any question relevant to ascertaining obedience or disobedience to the conditions imposed may the Attorney General ask those questions and failure to answer them be followed by the consequence, isn't that the problem?","start":1200.67,"stop":1217.004,"duration":16.33}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that's -- that's exactly the problem.","start":1217.004,"stop":1219.351,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Davis, let's get back to these six months.","start":1219.351,"stop":1223.735,"duration":4.38},{"text":"What's the purpose of allowing the Attorney General to confine for six months?","start":1223.735,"stop":1230.699,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's a strong feeling in certain congressmen or senators that the way to protect the country from these deportable aliens who had been ordered deported was to confine, keep them in concentration camps or -- or somewhere else to keep them under control.","start":1230.699,"stop":1250.407,"duration":19.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, if I may interrupt you just a moment.","start":1250.407,"stop":1253.173,"duration":2.77},{"text":"Now, basically, the idea was until we can work out the details of getting them out of here, let's keep our eyes on them, have them somewhere where we can keep our eyes of them, is that it?","start":1253.173,"stop":1266.073,"duration":12.9}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1266.073,"stop":1266.712,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, I take it the obligation at the end of six months to release on the supervisory order, that doesn't change that purpose on it, does it?","start":1266.712,"stop":1277.173,"duration":10.46}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That doesn't change the purpose, that's right.","start":1277.173,"stop":1278.661,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that I gather your position is we have to focus our attention on what was done here inclusive of the questions that were asked in light of the purpose to do the same thing that confinement initially for six months --","start":1278.661,"stop":1295.159,"duration":16.5}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1295.159,"stop":1295.697,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was in fact --","start":1295.697,"stop":1296.111,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1296.111,"stop":1296.798,"duration":0.69},{"text":"That is right, Your Honor.","start":1296.798,"stop":1299.155,"duration":2.36},{"text":"And that question -- the question would be the same.","start":1299.155,"stop":1301.36,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Is confinement solely for the purpose of making the alien available at the dock at the time you want him to go or is the confinement intended also for the purpose of preventing this kind of activity by which he is being before this?","start":1301.36,"stop":1315.424,"duration":14.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me ask this.","start":1315.424,"stop":1318.319,"duration":2.89},{"text":"The -- does it make any difference in the exercise by the Attorney General whether or not to confine for six months what the reason was that the alien is being deported?","start":1318.319,"stop":1329.547,"duration":11.23},{"text":"For example, as I understand it, there might be a deportable alien.","start":1329.547,"stop":1333.438,"duration":3.89},{"text":"We had a case argued here just a couple of weeks ago as I recall it that involved someone, a neutral alien who had sought --","start":1333.438,"stop":1343.466,"duration":10.03}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Suggested (Voice Overlap) --","start":1343.466,"stop":1343.869,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- exemption from the draft.","start":1343.869,"stop":1345.35,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it'd make a very great difference what -- what the -- what the reason for deportation was.","start":1345.35,"stop":1349.934,"duration":4.58},{"text":"This -- this question, Mr. Justice Brennan, of -- of when and how the Attorney General should exercise his authority was taken up rather exhaustively in this Court and in Carlson against Landon, the statute which says that the Attorney General was given authority to detain the alien during the proceeding and the question was raised there.","start":1349.934,"stop":1370.59,"duration":20.66},{"text":"Is the purpose of the detention in order to make him available or is it a broader purpose?","start":1370.59,"stop":1375.893,"duration":5.3},{"text":"And I may say that both the majority and a dissent and there's a strong dissent from the case.","start":1375.893,"stop":1380.761,"duration":4.87},{"text":"Both the majority and the dissent referred to the element of safeguarding the security of United States from his activities, not being sure that if he's here he's here too much, but safeguarding the United States from his activities.","start":1380.761,"stop":1395.196,"duration":14.43},{"text":"And that was considered by this Court to be a proper element in the -- in retaining him in custody.","start":1395.196,"stop":1402.35,"duration":7.15},{"text":"And if I may say so, it's the -- it's really the strongest part of my argument this morning that if it is a proper element in considering whether or not to -- to keep the man confined, it seems to me that this element of security of preventing him from carrying on these activities is a proper element of the --","start":1402.35,"stop":1423.513,"duration":21.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, in this case however, I think you said he was out on bail.","start":1423.513,"stop":1427.492,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He was out on bail.","start":1427.492,"stop":1428.283,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How long at -- at all during the six months period was he confined?","start":1428.283,"stop":1434.846,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think he was confined at any time during the six months.","start":1434.846,"stop":1436.977,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now what supervision was he put under while he was on bail?","start":1436.977,"stop":1441.498,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- I don't know what the conditions of the bond were.","start":1441.498,"stop":1444.337,"duration":2.84},{"text":"They're not on the record and I do not know them.","start":1444.337,"stop":1447.379,"duration":3.04},{"text":"He was released on a -- on a $5000 bond and I don't know --","start":1447.379,"stop":1451.36,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my point is that he was allowed to roam free without any supervisions for six months on a $5000 bond.","start":1451.36,"stop":1458.167,"duration":6.81},{"text":"It seems a little inconsistent to put him under a stringent supervision --","start":1458.167,"stop":1461.651,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- well, that may be so.","start":1461.651,"stop":1466.121,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I -- I -- it -- although the Attorney General was given authority in these cases to -- to change his position to release the man without bond and then to put him on -- under bond it's that he's not -- the Attorney General waives no -- no authority in this matter by not imposing a condition in the first place.","start":1466.121,"stop":1484.831,"duration":18.71},{"text":"It may -- it may raise a question and in our minds as to whether the -- the condition is necessary.","start":1484.831,"stop":1491.186,"duration":6.36},{"text":"But it's not a question of -- of authority.","start":1491.186,"stop":1493.7,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Davis, under the law, does the Court have the right in -- in admitting a man to bail to subjecting to -- to all these conditions that -- that Attorney General subjects into after the six months?","start":1493.7,"stop":1509.922,"duration":16.22},{"text":"Would it be -- would it be a valid release on bail if they put those restrictions on him?","start":1509.922,"stop":1518.664,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think it must depend on -- on the particular statute involved, generally speaking.","start":1518.664,"stop":1523.797,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, take this one.","start":1523.797,"stop":1525.772,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this --","start":1525.772,"stop":1526.451,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In this (Voice Overlap) --","start":1526.451,"stop":1527.027,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in this -- in this case, the -- the bond is I think these would be proper conditions for the -- for the bond on the release during the six months.","start":1527.027,"stop":1537.742,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You do think it is?","start":1537.742,"stop":1538.494,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1538.494,"stop":1538.996,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's what I think.","start":1538.996,"stop":1539.629,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that this would be and I think the terms of the bond would -- would receive contempt from this later supervisor -- supervisory order, the provision for the supervisory order.","start":1539.629,"stop":1550.195,"duration":10.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"As the matter of the words, it's your position that the Court did say in the first instance when he's ordered deported, I'll admit you to bail with the sum of $5000 provided you -- you submit yourself to the Attorney General and answer all questions --","start":1550.195,"stop":1563.447,"duration":13.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1563.447,"stop":1563.728,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and do all things that -- that the statute requires that you can -- you must do after the six months period.","start":1563.728,"stop":1571.212,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"This bond with one -- with one amendment, that this bond is provided by the Attorney General not by the Court I mean in this period.","start":1571.212,"stop":1577.147,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, can he -- can the Attorney General provide such a bond?","start":1577.147,"stop":1580.294,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's -- and my answer was the Attorney General could but I think he should in these circumstances.","start":1580.294,"stop":1584.523,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does --","start":1584.523,"stop":1584.644,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact, Mr. Brennan's question would indicate that it -- we've done it against it -- against the supervisory order if he didn't.","start":1584.644,"stop":1591.065,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well does -- does the Attorney General issue bond releases of that kind?","start":1591.065,"stop":1595.772,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally speaking, yes.","start":1595.772,"stop":1597.071,"duration":1.3},{"text":"They --","start":1597.071,"stop":1597.29,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"They could.","start":1597.29,"stop":1597.354,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I mean I can't say that they have these precise terms in them but that is the practice to condition and have the bond conditioned on -- on similar terms.","start":1597.354,"stop":1604.887,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On -- on what the man reads?","start":1604.887,"stop":1607.236,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I do not know that it does -- the supervisory order in this case didn't have anything to do with reading.","start":1607.236,"stop":1614.011,"duration":6.77},{"text":"And a investigator for the immigration service asked whether he had read it and I'm willing to concede for the purpose of this argument that he could that -- to refuse to answer that question.","start":1614.011,"stop":1625.728,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could he?","start":1625.728,"stop":1627.176,"duration":1.45},{"text":"The statute says whether or not related --","start":1627.176,"stop":1630.171,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think --","start":1630.171,"stop":1630.401,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) as the Attorney General deem fit and proper.","start":1630.401,"stop":1633.142,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it was an improper question and he could then refuse to answer it because it infringed on his rights under the First Amendment just as he could have refused possibly on some of the other questions on the Fifth Amendment.","start":1633.142,"stop":1643.26,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the constitutional ground, not the statutory.","start":1643.26,"stop":1645.978,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1645.978,"stop":1646.486,"duration":0.51},{"text":"Well, statutorily that may be a real pertinence in asking him whether he's read -- whether he reads the Daily Worker, Your Honor.","start":1646.486,"stop":1653.015,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's say the --","start":1653.015,"stop":1653.355,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Constitutionally, I'm not sure that the -- that relevancy should be called.","start":1653.355,"stop":1657.499,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I have some trouble following that at least for the six months period.","start":1657.499,"stop":1662.835,"duration":5.34},{"text":"Suppose these very questions were imposed that in connection with the conditions imposed that he had to report to the Attorney General if he was to remain on bail.","start":1662.835,"stop":1673.259,"duration":10.42},{"text":"And the question were put to him, do you read The Daily Worker?","start":1673.259,"stop":1675.707,"duration":2.45},{"text":"And he said, “I won't answer it.”","start":1675.707,"stop":1676.902,"duration":1.19},{"text":"And they said, “All right, that's your bail bond.","start":1676.902,"stop":1679.308,"duration":2.41},{"text":"In fact, you go to prison.”","start":1679.308,"stop":1681.033,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Would he have any --","start":1681.033,"stop":1681.826,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think he'd have the right in habeas corpus.","start":1681.826,"stop":1683.685,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You think he would?","start":1683.685,"stop":1684.773,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":1684.773,"stop":1685.454,"duration":0.68},{"text":"I would think it was an impassive -- that if you read the question back into the bonds, I don't think it is a proper question.","start":1685.454,"stop":1691.75,"duration":6.3},{"text":"I think that's the trouble with it but if you read it back into the bond and then he had a right to refuse to answer and there was an improper condition then he could be released on habeas corpus.","start":1691.75,"stop":1700.556,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose he had -- suppose he had after he'd been ordered deported joined in the Communist Party, would he have committed a crime?","start":1700.556,"stop":1708.696,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":1708.696,"stop":1711.298,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And what can you inquire about --","start":1711.298,"stop":1715.23,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this might -- our basic argument in this case, Your Honor is that this isn't -- this isn't a punishment.","start":1715.23,"stop":1722.549,"duration":7.32},{"text":"We're not punishing the -- the alien by putting him under this restraint.","start":1722.549,"stop":1728.518,"duration":5.97},{"text":"He is -- he is a -- a person who Congress has said is conducting himself in such a way that he should be deported that this activity is what we do not want aliens to do.","start":1728.518,"stop":1739.663,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Now, Congress doesn't say that it's a crime that alien -- aliens do these things.","start":1739.663,"stop":1743.58,"duration":3.92},{"text":"They just say that if people are going to stay on this country and retain that foreign citizenship, there are certain things that if they do them, we feel they should leave the country.","start":1743.58,"stop":1753.825,"duration":10.25},{"text":"One of those things that they feel aliens should not do is to associate -- did join the Communist Party and associate with the Communist, you know that Congress whose intention on this is perfectly clear in the Internal Security Act and in the Immigration and Nationality Act.","start":1753.825,"stop":1768.514,"duration":14.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it really comes is out of this that you say that Congress as respects to deport an alien, to subject him to restrictions in the interest of national security that it could not from the statutes subject to a citizenship.","start":1768.514,"stop":1787.583,"duration":19.07}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think that is probably so.","start":1787.583,"stop":1790.084,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But then why do you make an exception in case of the First Amendment?","start":1790.084,"stop":1793.405,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there -- there is no question that aliens here are entitled to the protection of the Fifth Amendment and the First Amendment.","start":1793.405,"stop":1802.153,"duration":8.75},{"text":"And -- and I don't know what other constitutional rights, the right to trial by jury you can't take an alien and fine for murder without a jury.","start":1802.153,"stop":1809.723,"duration":7.57},{"text":"They're entitled to the protection of the Constitution as anybody else is.","start":1809.723,"stop":1812.959,"duration":3.24},{"text":"The question is whether this is an unreasonable restraint on this man's liberty that to require him to report, to require him to answer questions under these circumstances.","start":1812.959,"stop":1824.66,"duration":11.7},{"text":"And our point is basically this.","start":1824.66,"stop":1826.457,"duration":1.8},{"text":"That if it is -- if it is a legal thing, it's a constitutional thing to say this is so bad that the man shall be sent out of the country.","start":1826.457,"stop":1834.223,"duration":7.77},{"text":"If this is the kind of thing which is the kind of thing that this Court has said, he can be retained in custody while you -- while you -- confined, while you're -- while you're deciding it.","start":1834.223,"stop":1844.959,"duration":10.74},{"text":"It certainly is the kind of thing where it is not unreasonable to say that we shall have this kind of a supervision, this general supervision with respect to his activities.","start":1844.959,"stop":1854.638,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is your position that during the first six months, he must have bail to get out within that six months.","start":1854.638,"stop":1859.291,"duration":4.65},{"text":"He doesn't have to have bail but it's situation in relation to questions that is obtained in both (Inaudible)","start":1859.291,"stop":1863.937,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1863.937,"stop":1864.929,"duration":0.99},{"text":"Although I may say that specifically that question with respect to questions during the six months is not before the Court but that's -- I mean except there's a -- is it relevant in our -- our -- in our logic on it.","start":1864.929,"stop":1875.738,"duration":10.81},{"text":"But I think that that is so.","start":1875.738,"stop":1877.174,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, I -- I recognized you had temptations for this constitution experience, but why didn't you first dispose of the statutory question?","start":1877.174,"stop":1886.954,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I was about -- I was about to go into the statutory question because the courts below found that this Act -- this Act gave authority to the Attorney General only to ask questions with respect to the alien's availability, availability for deportation.","start":1886.954,"stop":1905.933,"duration":18.98},{"text":"And these questions obviously have nothing to do or are only collaterally relevant to whether he will be present when the time comes.","start":1905.933,"stop":1913.181,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I -- may I ask in order to search -- in order to understand what Judge Sullivan ruled.","start":1913.181,"stop":1918.719,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Do I understand that if the questions were solely directed to and relevant be limited to inquiries, whether he hasn't changed his -- his habitat was such was frequently and leaving no address behind at each change of residence or habitations whether you infer or have we tried to infer Judge Sullivan would say, “That's all right.”","start":1918.719,"stop":1949.995,"duration":31.28}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure he would say, “That's all right.”","start":1949.995,"stop":1952.348,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, as I understand you to say that the inquiry of the Attorney General should be limited to the reasons for the man's deportation that is it --","start":1952.348,"stop":1963.637,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It was.","start":1963.637,"stop":1963.776,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- must be in that field?","start":1963.776,"stop":1965.675,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say.I think they ought to be related to the order of supervision and -- and the supervision must order -- a supervision must be a -- a reasonable one.","start":1965.675,"stop":1974.852,"duration":9.18},{"text":"There must be some basis for it.","start":1974.852,"stop":1976.549,"duration":1.7},{"text":"It is possible that an alien would be -- would have been deported for -- of some crimes, sexual misbehavior or something and he also may have a record of being associated with -- with the Communist Party.","start":1976.549,"stop":1992.05,"duration":15.5},{"text":"And I think it would be entirely appropriate even though he was being deported for some other crimes if he has a record of association with the Communist Party that the supervisory order take that into consideration.","start":1992.05,"stop":2003.891,"duration":11.84},{"text":"But it's not present in this case because in this case, he was ordered deported for -- for associate -- for the communist activity.","start":2003.891,"stop":2010.952,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's take two -- two situations.","start":2010.952,"stop":2013.826,"duration":2.87},{"text":"One man is deported because of -- of his association with the Communist Party.","start":2013.826,"stop":2019.811,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2019.811,"stop":2020.493,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Another man is deported because he -- he has a conviction of narcotics.","start":2020.493,"stop":2027.965,"duration":7.47},{"text":"Now, would you say that the -- the man who was convicted of narcotics and who was deported for that conduct could not be under surveillance of the Attorney General for subversive activities while he is awaiting it or -- or -- and that the Attorney General would be limited to surveilling his conduct in relation to the narcotic traffic.","start":2027.965,"stop":2062.817,"duration":34.85}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- as a supervisory order, I think that is -- is that's right.","start":2062.817,"stop":2066.199,"duration":3.38},{"text":"I that -- this have to have some relations to the man's background that would have to deal with narcotics.","start":2066.199,"stop":2070.946,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So the -- the narcotic violator could become subversive and the -- and the subversive could become a narcotic.","start":2070.946,"stop":2078.86,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it --","start":2078.86,"stop":2079.621,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, without -- without interfering with the --","start":2079.621,"stop":2081.721,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a matter of reasonable cause.","start":2081.721,"stop":2083.772,"duration":2.05},{"text":"If the Attorney General had any reason to believe, these orders should have some reference to the -- as that the Court said in Carlson against Landon, you couldn't look at the -- the case to find out what is necessary in order to protect the -- the welfare of the United States with respect to these aliens.","start":2083.772,"stop":2100.437,"duration":16.66},{"text":"Now, if the man is convicted of narcotics and there's no reason to believe that he's engaged in -- in Communist activities, it's not reasonable to put him under restrictions at that time with respect to membership in the Communist Party.","start":2100.437,"stop":2112.288,"duration":11.85},{"text":"There's just no -- no reason to -- to restrict his liberty.","start":2112.288,"stop":2115.868,"duration":3.58},{"text":"However, if there is reasonable cause to believe that that's his activities will extend in that direction I should think it was well within the authority of the Attorney General to -- to issue a supervisory order and that with -- with that respect.","start":2115.868,"stop":2129.531,"duration":13.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's -- let's say that the narcotics violator had no background of -- of communism at all.","start":2129.531,"stop":2137.7,"duration":8.17},{"text":"But when he was under the surveillance of the Attorney General in this deportation proceeding, it was ascertained that he read The Daily Worker, that he went to this -- this place that -- to meetings.","start":2137.7,"stop":2151.319,"duration":13.62},{"text":"He associated with some known Communist and was -- was suspected of -- of being a Communist at that time.","start":2151.319,"stop":2160.365,"duration":9.05},{"text":"Will the Attorney General then have the right to say, “Now, I'm going to -- I'm going to keep you under surveillance as to your communistic activities and I'm going to require you to report to me on all your associations in that field.”","start":2160.365,"stop":2174.075,"duration":13.71}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":2174.075,"stop":2175.148,"duration":1.07},{"text":"I would think that --","start":2175.148,"stop":2175.736,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's --","start":2175.736,"stop":2176.198,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that would be my position.","start":2176.198,"stop":2176.873,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's your position.","start":2176.873,"stop":2177.629,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":2177.629,"stop":2178.031,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So then the words that Justice Black read from the -- from the Act do become very forceful, don't they?","start":2178.031,"stop":2185.426,"duration":7.39},{"text":"And in that anything that the Attorney General desires to inquire probably he has a right to do.","start":2185.426,"stop":2194.683,"duration":9.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He has the right to inquire about them, yes, but if you're going to convict the man of crime who's not answering, if there was no reason -- if the question was an unreasonable question or if it violated his constitutional rights, he has the right to refuse to answer.","start":2194.683,"stop":2210.02,"duration":15.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he might even -- he might even have been guilty of conduct --","start":2210.02,"stop":2212.438,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think in fact --","start":2212.438,"stop":2213.369,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it would --- it would be of a suspicious character that -- that under those circumstances, the -- the Attorney General would not be limited to any field.","start":2213.369,"stop":2222.58,"duration":9.21},{"text":"He could -- he could -- keeping him under surveillance for his entire time.","start":2222.58,"stop":2228.185,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Anytime that which he had reasonable cause to believe would -- would interfere -- would impinge on the safety of the -- of the nation.","start":2228.185,"stop":2238.037,"duration":9.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the statute contain any limitations at that time?","start":2238.037,"stop":2240.596,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it says -- it says any other -- any other matters whether related to the foregoing or not which the Attorney General deems fit and proper.","start":2240.596,"stop":2250.397,"duration":9.8},{"text":"And may I say that I read that limitation into the statute in the same way that this Court read the limitation and into the confinement provisions in Carlson against Landon where the Court said that the confinement must be read with reference to the objects of the Act.","start":2250.397,"stop":2268.121,"duration":17.72},{"text":"And so we build these questions, these -- the supervision and the questions must be related to the objects of the Act.","start":2268.121,"stop":2275.934,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how -- how do you get the objects of the Act limited to that?","start":2275.934,"stop":2279.654,"duration":3.72},{"text":"If it's to mean like object to Act is except that you give some subordinate to the Attorney General.","start":2279.654,"stop":2286,"duration":6.35},{"text":"This is done by a subordinate, wasn't it?","start":2286,"stop":2287.554,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was done.","start":2287.554,"stop":2288.8,"duration":1.25},{"text":"The questioning was --","start":2288.8,"stop":2288.922,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2288.922,"stop":2289.587,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- done by --","start":2289.587,"stop":2290.07,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what if you call people in and ask them when you get right here about anything if they want to ask him.","start":2290.07,"stop":2295.62,"duration":5.55},{"text":"That's part of the statute concerned kind of a paternalistic protection (Inaudible) so that you can have these people who were brought in.","start":2295.62,"stop":2305.157,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2305.157,"stop":2305.724,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Which may be all right but that's what it seems to me it did.","start":2305.724,"stop":2308.301,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the statute has a purpose, doesn't it?","start":2308.301,"stop":2309.814,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":2309.814,"stop":2310.622,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the deportation order is directed towards the ground for deportation.","start":2310.622,"stop":2316.483,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The deportation order is over.","start":2316.483,"stop":2318.594,"duration":2.11},{"text":"That's -- we -- that's not challenged, is it?","start":2318.594,"stop":2320.565,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but its (Voice Overlap) --","start":2320.565,"stop":2321.177,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2321.177,"stop":2322.596,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The only question here now is this, isn't it?","start":2322.596,"stop":2325.886,"duration":3.29},{"text":"This man's got to be deported.","start":2325.886,"stop":2327.301,"duration":1.41},{"text":"He can't be deported yet.","start":2327.301,"stop":2328.945,"duration":1.64},{"text":"For some reason, he can't get him in, can he?","start":2328.945,"stop":2331.134,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2331.134,"stop":2332.169,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And he's here.","start":2332.169,"stop":2333.896,"duration":1.73},{"text":"The statute says that during this time says the Attorney General as (Inaudible) but whoever he designates people work here can call him in and have him report on his nationality, circumstances, address, association or no activities and such other information whether or not related to foregoing (Inaudible)","start":2333.896,"stop":2358.881,"duration":24.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2358.881,"stop":2359.471,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So, where do you find anything that indicates there that the deportation order which is over and ready to be executed has anything to do with the objects of what we need to ask him?","start":2359.471,"stop":2370.191,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"You're quite right, Your Honor, that there is no limitation in -- in the words of the statute as to what questions can be asked.","start":2370.191,"stop":2377.672,"duration":7.48},{"text":"If one reads to this the -- this -- this language in -- in the light of the entire statute, one must assume he's going to ask questions which are in accordance with the -- the purpose of the statute just as in the Carlson --","start":2377.672,"stop":2389.955,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2389.955,"stop":2390.356,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- against Landon case.","start":2390.356,"stop":2391.325,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't see where the -- the question -- the -- the basis for the deportation has anything to do with it.","start":2391.325,"stop":2399.858,"duration":8.53},{"text":"I don't -- I don't see it.","start":2399.858,"stop":2400.543,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2400.543,"stop":2401.006,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe it had.","start":2401.006,"stop":2401.89,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the history of the -- of the purpose of -- of supervising is that aliens who had been ordered deported because of activities which were considered improper for aliens, they've been ordered sent out of this country were still here, 4000 doing, presumably free to do precisely the same things that they've been ordered sent out of the country for.","start":2401.89,"stop":2422.722,"duration":20.83},{"text":"Now, Congress said, \"How are we going to deal with this?","start":2422.722,"stop":2425.264,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Shall we prevent these aliens from -- from doing this conduct which we believe antisocial shall we prevent it by -- by keeping them in -- in confinement or shall we somehow try and keep an eye on them, something more elastic?","start":2425.264,"stop":2440.104,"duration":14.84},{"text":"Let them live with their families.","start":2440.104,"stop":2441.73,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Let them continue --","start":2441.73,"stop":2442.322,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2442.322,"stop":2442.535,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- within their work (Inaudible) but keep an eye on them --","start":2442.535,"stop":2444.962,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) than he is.","start":2444.962,"stop":2447.689,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2447.689,"stop":2448.069,"duration":0.38},{"text":"But --","start":2448.069,"stop":2448.144,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And what -- what do you have here is a man, then ordered deported, that's finished.","start":2448.144,"stop":2453.11,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":2453.11,"stop":2453.442,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And I would judge if what they're after is to have a constant fatherly supervision over these people in order to find out what they're doing and whether they go to the movies and -- and things of that kind.","start":2453.442,"stop":2465.518,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"To prevent them from doing --","start":2465.518,"stop":2466.956,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't suppose this man could have declined to answer the -- whether he's going to the movies in order to have -- might incriminate him.","start":2466.956,"stop":2472.363,"duration":5.41},{"text":"And this, certainly, all the questions you're talking about if he hadn't been an alien and subject to deportation, I would say that it'll be a little different to make (Inaudible)","start":2472.363,"stop":2480.832,"duration":8.47}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't know what the movie in question was and I don't know what the evidence would have been that the Court --","start":2480.832,"stop":2485.219,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You just ask about movies.","start":2485.219,"stop":2485.569,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- had wanted to have.","start":2485.569,"stop":2486.489,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And have you been to any movies though I'm not asking question.","start":2486.489,"stop":2493.16,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I would -- I would support if it -- if -- if pressed.","start":2493.16,"stop":2496.769,"duration":3.61},{"text":"I would support this case particularly on the questions which deal with are you a member of the Communist Party and --","start":2496.769,"stop":2503.433,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose he hadn't been an alien ordered deported and they call him up trying to make him tell under oath, \"What would do to the Blau case about that?\"","start":2503.433,"stop":2510.274,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if he -- if this man had claimed the privilege against incrimination as it was done in the Blau case, then you would have the question of whether he had the constitutional right of protection of the Fifth Amendment and I'm --","start":2510.274,"stop":2522.21,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he --","start":2522.21,"stop":2522.298,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- did well anticipate what the Court would do with the question.","start":2522.298,"stop":2525.264,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2525.264,"stop":2525.333,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But specifically, he did not claim the protection of the Fifth Amendment.","start":2525.333,"stop":2528.68,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, these examinations were held publicly or in secret?","start":2528.68,"stop":2531.463,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"In these -- these are held publicly and counsel was present.","start":2531.463,"stop":2536.486,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the -- does the Attorney General have authority to hold him secret?","start":2536.486,"stop":2539.723,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't know whether he does not or not.","start":2539.723,"stop":2542.754,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Should we imply that in order to have it declared unconstitutional?","start":2542.754,"stop":2545.754,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so.","start":2545.754,"stop":2546.987,"duration":1.23},{"text":"In this particular case, the evidence is perfectly clear that the counsel was present in representing (Inaudible)","start":2546.987,"stop":2553.173,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm delighted to have your views that we don't have to apply that I'm sure it's very relevant.","start":2553.173,"stop":2557.779,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could we eventually get to the statute, Mr. Davis, that construction brought the case here?","start":2557.779,"stop":2564.728,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The first place to look for the meaning of the statute I think is the word statute itself.","start":2564.728,"stop":2572.187,"duration":7.46},{"text":"And my first argument therefore would be that it isn't reasonable to read these words that the -- he must give information under oath with respect to his habits, associations and activities as words which would be designed to show whether or not he was -- would be available on the dock for deportation.","start":2572.187,"stop":2594.652,"duration":22.47},{"text":"They've sound to -- they sound like words that you would ask an alien to find out what he was doing rather than whether or not he was going to be available to be deported.","start":2594.652,"stop":2606.004,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose his wife was a Communist, could he get into that?","start":2606.004,"stop":2610.177,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the supervisory --","start":2610.177,"stop":2610.977,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he the --","start":2610.977,"stop":2611.506,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- order, he is given -- he is given authority to associate with his wife and his counsel even though they may be Communists.","start":2611.506,"stop":2618.877,"duration":7.37},{"text":"It's accepted from the -- from the supervisory order.","start":2618.877,"stop":2623.974,"duration":5.1},{"text":"The second -- the second clue we have to the meaning of this language is its -- its location in the statute.","start":2623.974,"stop":2631.303,"duration":7.33},{"text":"It -- it follows -- this section follows immediately after the section dealing with retaining an alien in custody.","start":2631.303,"stop":2641.54,"duration":10.24},{"text":"And as I mentioned before, that section was before this Court in Carlson against Landon 342 U.S.524.","start":2641.54,"stop":2650.878,"duration":9.34},{"text":"And presumably that the purposes of the strict custody of -- of retaining a man in confinement and the elastic custody that can be called out of -- of the supervisory order are -- are related.","start":2650.878,"stop":2667.644,"duration":16.77},{"text":"And this Court -- this Court, both the majority and the minority, specifically interpreted the custody provisions as in -- as authorizing the Attorney General to keep the man in confinement if he had reason to believe that it was necessary for the security of the United States.","start":2667.644,"stop":2688.561,"duration":20.92},{"text":"And the third way to find out the meaning of this statute I suppose is the legislative history and we speak with it at some length in our brief.","start":2688.561,"stop":2697.884,"duration":9.32},{"text":"The truth of the matter is that from 1939 and 1950, Representative Holmes pressed for legislation to protect the country from deportable aliens, not only submissives, but other aliens guilty of other -- of other offenses to protect the country from -- of their presence here when they've been ordered deported and couldn't be deported.","start":2697.884,"stop":2721.856,"duration":23.97},{"text":"And when he was finally able to -- to get this enacted into law was when the Internal Security Act was passed.","start":2721.856,"stop":2730.666,"duration":8.81},{"text":"This provision was originally a section of the Internal Security Act and it this was well known, the prime object of that Act was to protect this country against communist activities.","start":2730.666,"stop":2745.43,"duration":14.76},{"text":"Now, in the legislative history, we have a presidential message.","start":2745.43,"stop":2750.231,"duration":4.8},{"text":"We have a recommendation from the Department of Justice.","start":2750.231,"stop":2753.519,"duration":3.29},{"text":"We have reports from the judiciary committees of both Houses.","start":2753.519,"stop":2757.708,"duration":4.19},{"text":"We have statements by Representative Holmes on -- on from the floor.","start":2757.708,"stop":2761.827,"duration":4.12},{"text":"And they all, without exception, tie the supervision of these aliens in with the question of their continued antisocial activity rather than with their availability for deportation.","start":2761.827,"stop":2775.962,"duration":14.13},{"text":"And if there were -- if there were further need for -- for interpreting the statute, I might point out that this provision was reenacted by Congress in 1952.","start":2775.962,"stop":2787.311,"duration":11.35},{"text":"It originally passed as part of the Internal Security Act in 1950.","start":2787.311,"stop":2791.901,"duration":4.59},{"text":"After that, this Court construed the custody provisions in Carlson against Landon.","start":2791.901,"stop":2797.301,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And after that, the Court reenacted -- the Congress reenacted the section in 1952 so that we have here a case of reenactment of -- of this provision after interpretation by the Court.","start":2797.301,"stop":2812.835,"duration":15.53},{"text":"It seems -- it seems clear to me that the court below must have reached its interpretation because it felt that unless it limited the statute to availability for deportation, it would have grave constitutional questions as to whether that was a power under the Constitution to -- to hold the -- to hold the alien.","start":2812.835,"stop":2834.057,"duration":21.22},{"text":"But I think it's of somewhat doubtful humanity to mutilate a statute by cutting off two arms and a leg in order to uphold the remnant.","start":2834.057,"stop":2845.602,"duration":11.55},{"text":"If we are right, the Congress clearly intended the Attorney General to have power -- supervisory power over activity, by then the Court was stepping into the legislative field when it interpreted the statute as it did.","start":2845.602,"stop":2860.076,"duration":14.47},{"text":"And it seems -- it seems clear to us that the statute as written is constitutional.","start":2860.076,"stop":2869.065,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean as interpreted like you said.","start":2869.065,"stop":2872.857,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, as -- as written and as -- as interpreted by the Court in Carlson against Landon which I translate to this case.","start":2872.857,"stop":2882.606,"duration":9.75},{"text":"The basic constitutional issue is -- and the appellee restates it in -- in many guises, but the basic constitutional issue is whether the exercise of supervisory restraints over these aliens deprives them of liberty without due process of law.","start":2882.606,"stop":2900.849,"duration":18.24},{"text":"The argument is that they have not been found guilty of any crime and indeed this alien hasn't been found guilty -- guilty of any crime.","start":2900.849,"stop":2907.77,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And that therefore, any attempt to restrict his activity is a punishment which is imposed upon him without indictment, jury trial or the other safeguards of the criminal law.","start":2907.77,"stop":2920.272,"duration":12.5},{"text":"And if these were a punishment, if the aim and -- and the result of this kind of a supervisory order were a punishment, I believe the statute would be unconstitutional.","start":2920.272,"stop":2931.507,"duration":11.24},{"text":"In similar situation, the -- the -- this Court upset a -- a Immigration Act way back in 1896 in Wong Wing against United States which was a case of imprisoning Chinese without jury trial, without any trial in administrative imprisonment.","start":2931.507,"stop":2949.679,"duration":18.17},{"text":"And the Court had no difficulty in saying that that was a punishment and that it should -- that the -- and was unconstitutional.","start":2949.679,"stop":2957.771,"duration":8.09},{"text":"But the -- this type of restraint which we have in this case is not imposed as -- as a punishment.","start":2957.771,"stop":2964.737,"duration":6.97},{"text":"It is imposed because there is some necessity of -- of preventing aliens which have been found engaged in antisocial activities and ordered deported from continuing to perform the same activities in the interim before they can finally be removed.","start":2964.737,"stop":2983.641,"duration":18.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, I'm a little puzzled by your mode of arguments here.","start":2983.641,"stop":2989.363,"duration":5.72},{"text":"We haven't this before us restraint, any restraint, any confinement.","start":2989.363,"stop":2996.304,"duration":6.94},{"text":"We have before us a basis of -- of criminal charge derived from the claim of the Government, of the right of the Attorney General to ask questions.","start":2996.304,"stop":3012.663,"duration":16.36},{"text":"Surely they have subordinate asking.","start":3012.663,"stop":3015.883,"duration":3.22},{"text":"The Attorney General is given enough power and I at -- myself oh, I would restrict that to certain cases.","start":3015.883,"stop":3021.792,"duration":5.91},{"text":"So that if the question here is restraint the -- the narrow question as I see it is whether he -- the Congress may authorize him to ask questions and if he has the right -- if Congress may so authorize him to ask question then making disobedience of such a lawful order, for purposes of the question an offense I think that the latter isn't troublesome if the Congress of the United States can give that authority to the Attorney General then disobedience of such an authority may within the restrictions of the -- call them unusual punishment, these followed by legal consequences.","start":3021.792,"stop":3061.628,"duration":39.84},{"text":"So, I don't know why you're talking about restraint.","start":3061.628,"stop":3064.473,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3064.473,"stop":3064.539,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the whole point about that Judge Sullivan's opinion is that in as much as he can't do anything or Congress hasn't provided for the doing anything in case of disobedience of his restrictions except to make him talk, what?","start":3064.539,"stop":3084.428,"duration":19.89}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that's not quite so.","start":3084.428,"stop":3085.72,"duration":1.29},{"text":"I mean --","start":3085.72,"stop":3085.794,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, what -- I -- I asked you a little while ago.","start":3085.794,"stop":3087.52,"duration":1.73},{"text":"What can he do that -- that --","start":3087.52,"stop":3089.056,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3089.056,"stop":3089.159,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Sullivan says no matter what happened he can't do anything about it.","start":3089.159,"stop":3092.216,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":3092.216,"stop":3092.599,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What he can do?","start":3092.599,"stop":3093.774,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That the supervisory order orders the alien not to engage in Communist activities and not to associate with Communists.","start":3093.774,"stop":3102.201,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3102.201,"stop":3102.799,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And if he does associate with Communists, if he does participate in Communist activity, he violates the supervisory order which is also a crime and he can go to jail for one year.","start":3102.799,"stop":3113.333,"duration":10.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that isn't question here --","start":3113.333,"stop":3114.653,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It isn't in question here --","start":3114.653,"stop":3115.819,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what is violated, that all I'm saying is that the --","start":3115.819,"stop":3118.756,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":3118.756,"stop":3118.925,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the proceedings -- the proceedings relating to the inquiry doesn't authorize the Attorney General to do anything if he disobeys --","start":3118.925,"stop":3129.239,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh --","start":3129.239,"stop":3129.656,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- except that he subjects him to criminal prosecution.","start":3129.656,"stop":3134.089,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"On -- on the query, on the question?","start":3134.089,"stop":3135.775,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3135.775,"stop":3136.135,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's right.","start":3136.135,"stop":3136.671,"duration":0.54},{"text":"He can.","start":3136.671,"stop":3137.657,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that -- we haven't before us a case of -- of allegedly unlawful restraint.","start":3137.657,"stop":3143.017,"duration":5.36},{"text":"We have before us a challenge to the authority to ask question, disobedience to which these are made an offense and therefore we are drawn back out of the question whether Congress may impose such a duty upon a deportable alien.","start":3143.017,"stop":3160.892,"duration":17.88}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3160.892,"stop":3160.962,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's all the question is, isn't it?","start":3160.962,"stop":3163.016,"duration":2.05},{"text":"And that (Voice Overlap) --","start":3163.016,"stop":3163.277,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it depends where you've kept -- where you've kept the question off.","start":3163.277,"stop":3166.412,"duration":3.13},{"text":"I -- I have approached the -- the questions as part of the general supervisory scheme because I think they are an inherent part of it.","start":3166.412,"stop":3175.499,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":3175.499,"stop":3175.713,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"They gain strength from it then it gains strength from them that they're almost indivisible.","start":3175.713,"stop":3180.448,"duration":4.73},{"text":"But --","start":3180.448,"stop":3180.531,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I have to decide in this case -- in passing on the construction-- on passing on this, the judgment of Judge Sullivan, the question whether Congress could make disobedience of the conditions which the Attorney General imposed at the end of six months an offense.","start":3180.531,"stop":3198.798,"duration":18.27},{"text":"Is that also in the Court?","start":3198.798,"stop":3199.724,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think you're right, Your Honor.","start":3199.724,"stop":3201.066,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I think the narrow question before us is simply the question of --","start":3201.066,"stop":3203.106,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then why do we go all over these to me, rather difficult.","start":3203.106,"stop":3206.875,"duration":3.77},{"text":"I hope they are to others difficult constitutional questions.","start":3206.875,"stop":3210.819,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the reason that I --","start":3210.819,"stop":3212.109,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"At least until we get through knowing what the statute means.","start":3212.109,"stop":3215.356,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless -- unless --","start":3215.356,"stop":3216.015,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless Judge Sullivan is right as an end of the matter, isn't there.","start":3216.015,"stop":3219.252,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but unless these questions -- I may be arguing slightly against myself but unless these questions have some relevance to a supervisory order which is proper, by then, it would seem that the Attorney General had no -- there were no restrictions on his right to ask questions.","start":3219.252,"stop":3234.446,"duration":15.19},{"text":"And so I find --","start":3234.446,"stop":3235.187,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But they must -- certainly, they must -- certainly, the questions must be made relevant to what Congress has authorized and this Court has already sustained the power of the Attorney General to say at the end of six -- not the power -- the power of Congress --","start":3235.187,"stop":3250.179,"duration":14.99}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3250.179,"stop":3250.26,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to say at the end of six months, you're out.","start":3250.26,"stop":3252.937,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3252.937,"stop":3253.1,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But we're going to keep an eye on you because we want to deport if Yugoslavia opens up.","start":3253.1,"stop":3257.343,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And then is it proper to ask a man questions.","start":3257.343,"stop":3259.217,"duration":1.87},{"text":"That's -- that's the narrower question before this Court.","start":3259.217,"stop":3260.994,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then -- I had supposed, I don't know.","start":3260.994,"stop":3263.763,"duration":2.77},{"text":"This may be just be a simple --","start":3263.763,"stop":3264.571,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is right.","start":3264.571,"stop":3265.696,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- narrowness of mind that we ought to stick to --","start":3265.696,"stop":3267.222,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3267.222,"stop":3267.451,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- such narrow questions.","start":3267.451,"stop":3269.484,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is the narrowest ground on which this can be sustained.","start":3269.484,"stop":3272.762,"duration":3.28},{"text":"I would -- I would --","start":3272.762,"stop":3273.56,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or not sustained.","start":3273.56,"stop":3274.675,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Or not sustained.","start":3274.675,"stop":3275.695,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I -- I'm arguing on this private offense.","start":3275.695,"stop":3278.388,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I understand that but --","start":3278.388,"stop":3279.891,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Make right.","start":3279.891,"stop":3280.572,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's not -- but if it's not yet whether if it's not sustained, where do we go then?","start":3280.572,"stop":3284.951,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's not -- if these questions are not sustained --","start":3284.951,"stop":3286.784,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if Judge Sullivan's interpretation is not accepted, where do we go then?","start":3286.784,"stop":3292.911,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in that case since the indictment is dismissed then I suppose then it's a question of --","start":3292.911,"stop":3297.995,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Or in his -- in his -- suppose his interpretation is not accepted, we do not agree that -- that what he said that --","start":3297.995,"stop":3307.797,"duration":9.8}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3307.797,"stop":3307.916,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- all you can ask him about is questions concerning his availability.","start":3307.916,"stop":3311.844,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if it is -- if it were -- certainly, if -- if this Court should uphold Judge Sullivan on the ground that only questions with respect to availability were -- were properly asked, I would assume that was an interpretation by this Court if that was the purpose of supervision and that the entire supervision would be --","start":3311.844,"stop":3327.349,"duration":15.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3327.349,"stop":3327.944,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"-- limited to availability.","start":3327.944,"stop":3329.15,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But Justice Black assumes that we disagree with Judge --","start":3329.15,"stop":3331.692,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose we do agree with him.","start":3331.692,"stop":3332.58,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Judge Sullivan and you've already answered that.","start":3332.58,"stop":3335.142,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's also unconstitutional to ask these questions.","start":3335.142,"stop":3338.218,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I said suppose we disagree with Judge Sullivan.","start":3338.218,"stop":3340.543,"duration":2.33},{"text":"I'd like to have your judgment not mine or anybody else.","start":3340.543,"stop":3344.602,"duration":4.06},{"text":"I'd like to have your judgment as to what then we have to then we have to (Inaudible) something.","start":3344.602,"stop":3349.527,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you have to pass upon the constitutionality of asking -- of requiring of --","start":3349.527,"stop":3353.074,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We've already said that we don't have to.","start":3353.074,"stop":3356.075,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I said that you've had -- excuse me Your Honor.","start":3356.075,"stop":3358.74,"duration":2.66},{"text":"I was about to say that you'd have to pass upon the constitutionality of giving the Attorney General the authority to ask these questions and make the answer of crime.","start":3358.74,"stop":3367.245,"duration":8.51},{"text":"And that's the narrow question that you would be --","start":3367.245,"stop":3368.822,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well but you've said where is -- I put to you question.","start":3368.822,"stop":3371.732,"duration":2.91},{"text":"It's very obvious.","start":3371.732,"stop":3373.321,"duration":1.59},{"text":"Assume we disagree with Judge Sullivan, maybe (A) maybe raise questions of the constitutionality.","start":3373.321,"stop":3380.102,"duration":6.78},{"text":"Secondly, should we?","start":3380.102,"stop":3381.973,"duration":1.87},{"text":"And it's not for you to say whether we should --","start":3381.973,"stop":3383.944,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"You are quite right.","start":3383.944,"stop":3384.385,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's for us to say.","start":3384.385,"stop":3385.401,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"My -- my mind didn't advert to the -- the question of whether you would return it to the lower court.","start":3385.401,"stop":3393.825,"duration":8.42}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Feb 28, 1957","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"295","citation":"353 US 194 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/353/194","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Apr 29, 1957"}